author: GBarrington
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 8, 2024
content: I'm experimenting with replacing my Windows PC with a higher end tablet.  so I wanted a docking station  (let's call it the DS) to connect it to a mouse, keyboard, and most i importantly, my 28 inch display screen.  So Far, So Good!  This review is going through the docking station, the S9, and DEX, then displayed on a nice big screen!  I REALLY like using a REAL keyboard!Once it was delivered, I rushed to my workstation to see how it worked.  And it didn't!  Nothing, NOTHING would work.  It kept telling me to check the cables.  So out of frustration, I had lunch.It turned out that the case I bought for the S9 fooled me into thinking I had the DS plugged into the tablet, but it was not.  Once I had figured THAT out, the docking station, and the tablet worked well together.I like that I'm using two different RF Dongles for the keyboard and mouse plugged into the DS.  I don't have to use battery power to use Bluetooth for those accessories.  Plus, I still have one USB 3.0 port free.  The Keyboard and Mouse don't appear to lag, at all.  If it does, it is so minor that I am unable to percieve it.I like that I can power the Tablet from the DS.  I'm using a 20 watt Amazon charger, and it seems to work just fine.  The tablet doesn't give me any messages that I'm on a slow charge and it seems to charge as it does without the DS.The only real negative is that the cable from the DS to the Tab S9 is a bit too short for the tablet to be propped upright.  The tablet display remains on, and the S Pen can be used with it.  I'm thinking that I might want to use the tablet itself as a sort of touchpad sometimes.  I might find applications where I would want the tablet display to remain upright.  I don't know, but it MIGHT be a problem, maybe.Build quality seems good.  I think the DS case is metal, at least it looks and feels like aluminum.  And the cord going to the Tablet seems quite robust.  I can't comment yet on reliabiy,  It will take some time for that info to appear.  But functionally, it is everything the seller claims it is.  I am satisfied.

author: Randall R. Brachmann
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 10, 2024
content: I needed a powered port expander for my DELL laptop.  I was having issues with data/communication to my printer and I read that a powered port extender would solve this.  This is the right tool for the job with a few caveats.  The multi-port is solid and well built and lightweight for travel.  My new DELL Inspiron 16 uses a smart power adapter.  The system must have a minimum of 65 watts to boot up.  When I attach the power adapter to the muli-port and then the multi-port to the laptop, get a message about a weak charge (see attached photo).  Working with the vendor and their support team, we tried several options.  They even sent me a 2nd unit at no added charge.  Sadly, the problem was still showing.  I suspect the smart power adaptor is sensing the draw of the multi-port regardless of the laptop and stepping down to a lower wattage.  Ultimately, I connected the power adapter directly to the laptop and then used a spare power adapter just for the multi-port.  My laptop now reboots properly and I have the powered multi-port I needed to support an additional display (HDMI), HP Desk Jet (USB 3.0), I-Book (standalone hard drive), a spare USB 3.0 port for thumb drive, and a port for my original non-powered 4-port USB extender which I still use for my free-standing keyboard, and my laptop vent (fan) system.  The USB-C cable used to connect the multi-port to the laptop is about 5 inches long, so I had some rearranging to make this spaghetti mess to workout.  I'm told it's to minimize data loss/corruption to drives, monitors, etc.  Everything now works great.The support team was very helpful and patient.  Never condescending or argumentative.  They responded to my original review the next day and offered a refund or a new device while we worked on the problem.  I kept the device and didn't seek a refund.  I'm very happy with them.  Do I wish it worked with the laptop adapter instead of a 2nd adapter?  Sure, but I don't see this as their problem but something with the DELL.

author: Scott
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 28, 2020
content: This is an effective product to add functionality to my Surface Pro 7. I have a Kensington case for the computer because I take it into the field occasionally, and this works with the case on without a problem. I have seen other options that plug in to both the USB-A (regular USB) and USB-C (phone-charger-style USB) ports to give USB-C passthrough functionality, but those wouldn't work with my case. I use the HDMI port daily for a second monitor, and I use the ethernet port periodically if I have to uplink in one of our offices. Both ports seem to work without fail. The fact that each USB port on here is USB 3.0 is a huge selling point. The only thing I haven't used on this device is the power-delivery USB-C port, but I'm sure it would work just fine if I tried. The unit is aluminum but feels sturdy without being heavy.There is one concern with this device for me, and that's the cord. It is about 4 inches long from device to plug, and the device itself is another 4-ish inches. The port is 6" from the bottom of the computer. As a result, the device doesn't sit flat on the desktop, but rather at somewhat of an angle, and I believe that causes strain at the port plug. If the cord were just two, maybe three inches longer, the device would sit flat without any concern. Obviously this concern applies only to tablet-style or 2-in-1 computers, because laptops have their ports flush with the desk. But for me, it drops a star because it's unnecessary stress at the port, which could eventually wear out the connection. (That's supposedly not an issue for USB-C, but I'm skeptical.)Overall, best purchase for the money for my purposes. Would buy again, even with the 4 inch cord.

author: Tech Tango
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2018
content: This adapter packs a lot of features into a small 12cm device, and is perfectly usable as a portable "mini-Dock".Linux?  Windows 10?  Android?  Yes!The design is a sleek metal case, seamless, with no visible screws.Slender, with no parts to lose, takes up very little space in the bag -- about as much as two Sharpie pens.It has a captive 6-inch cable with USB-C, and connections for USB-C PD, HDMI, Ethernet, and three USB 3.0 (blue) sockets.  Inside is a USB Hub, Ethernet Adapter, and HDMI display (&audio) output.The HDMI output is driven by your computer's internal graphics adapter, so the second monitor is integrated into both Windows and Linux with no additional drivers.  I believe it's done with a Via Labs VL100 "Billboard" Display Alternate mode adapter for USB-C, so it adds a second Monitor/Display instance, but not a new Display Adapter.The USB xHCI hub (VIA Labs 2109:0817 VL812 Super Speed Hub) appears on the bus, and this provides the three open USB ports as well as the new Ethernet Controller.  It's a Realtek USB GbE Family Controller:  VID: 0bda and PID: 8153.  Drivers were automatically available in both Ubuntu Linux and Windows 10.  It linked up to a 1Gb Ethernet as normal, no prompts or settings needed.For the adventurous, this UtechSmart device also works with the Samsung Galaxy S9+, and surprisingly well!Plug a USB Thumbdrive into the ports and it appears as a Storage Device, perfect for copying pictures off the phone.The Ethernet works as well, and automatically gets a DHCP address and switches over to wired connection.The HDMI monitor shows a clone of the Galaxy S9+ screen in perfect detail.  Best to rotate the phone to horizontal to make the most of the monitor.  (Sorry, no Samsung Dex environment here, but a USB Mouse and Keyboard work just fine.)Powering the adapter also charges the phone, as expected, but not as fast as a direct connection.  I was more impressed that the phone happily powered the whole adapter, with HDMI, Ethernet, and USB from its own battery, no problem.I was going to poke fun at the whole Phone + Adapter + Monitor, Ethernet, USB Drive, Keyboard, Mouse, but now that it's been running for a while on my desk, I'm imagining it could be useful if you intend to be at your phone for hours, hammering out email or Amazon reviews.All in all, this is a really nice piece of kit to have in your travel bag, or as a single-connection desktop dock.  It has replaced my USB-On-The-Go (OTG) adapters, as those were always a bit sketchy with some USB devices, and prevented charging..  Even if I don't need all the features, it's small enough on the bag that it's replaced a number of other adapters already.I accepted an offer to test and review this device, and received it for free, but this is my honest and unbiased review.  Pictures are my own.

author: AMC
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 22, 2019
content: I gave this 5 stars because even though it isn't perfect, I think any issues I've encountered are more likely a result of the hardware, software, and drivers I'm using.  TL;DR: It basically works as expected and I can confirm that it doesn't use DisplayLink.  I contacted UTechSmart before purchase to confirm if this device used USB-C HDMI Alt-mode instead of a DisplayLink chip.  They confirmed it uses the former and said that though they had not tested it with a Pocket 2, if it didn't work I could return it no questions asked.  Bonus points to them for that.  For reference, I'm using it with a GPD Pocket 2 (late 2018 product refresh using an Intel m3-8100Y CPU), running Windows 10 LTSC 2019 and a mixture of GPD and first-party drivers (mostly direct from Intel and Realtek).  This is not how it comes from GPD, and is most definitely NOT a supported configuration by either GPD or Microsoft.  I'm using the latest Intel drivers available (26.20.100.7000) from the Intel site.  The only persistent issue is that on my device, if second-screen mode default (Win+P) is set to duplicate or extend then neither screen will display when the hub is first plugged in.  After a few seconds one of the screens will start working again.  If the default is second screen only then it will work immediately.  Once external display is working, using the Win+P shortcut to switch to duplicate or extend works correctly.  This is most likely a Windows or driver issue.  For reference the Pocket 2 has a 1920x1200 screen that I use at 150% scaling and I mostly used 1920x1080 @100% scale monitors for testing.  No HDMI adapters were used and I tested with two different known-good cables.  Monitors tested were two Dell S2240L, one LG IPS234, and a Panasonic TCP50GT25.  I also tested on a 4k Samsung UN50NU6950 and it reported output 4k@30fps, which is close enough to the Intel UHD 615 spec for HDMI 1.4.  This hub can function without external power, but if you have problems, try connecting power before you connect it to your computer.  When I used it for the first time, it wouldn't appear to work without external power, but after some unrelated software and driver updates, now it does.  For me, this issue was definitely on the host side, not the hub side.  The network chip is a Realtek RTL8153 USB 3 to gigabit Ethernet adapter.  I own several devices that use this chip and it is serviceable, but tends to reset or drop out under sustained gigabit traffic.  This is a characteristic of either the chip or Realtek's drivers, and there isn't really anything UTechSmart can do about it.  (The other common providers of low cost USB->Ethernet chips (e.g. the ASIX AX88179) often have the same problems.)  Below max speed, the 8153 works without any problems.  As an aside, if you have one of these chips in a standalone usb adapter, you can plug it into a USB 2 port to get a trouble-free 250-350 Mb/s without having to babysit it.I haven't tried stress-testing how much power you can get from the USB 3.0 ports, nor have I tried to saturate the USB-C link with simultaneous video, network, and USB SSD file transfer traffic.  It doesn't really fit my use case for the device, and if doing so didn't work or caused the hub to drop connection it wouldn't necessarily be the hub's fault anyway.  One feature of the GPD Pocket 2 is that it can charge from any 5V source, not just from a USB-C PD charger.  So I tried to power the hub with a regular USB power bank that can output 5V@1.8A (Soshine E3S).  When charging directly, the Pocket 2 increases current draw until the voltage begins to sag below 5V.  This is normal behavior and prevents the device from pulling too much current from the charger.  But when I power the hub and indirectly charge the device, the power bank's over-current protection immediately trips.  For whatever reason, the hub prevents the Pocket 2 from noticing the voltage drop in time to prevent a fault.  A higher output 5V source, or a proper USB-C PD power bank would probably work just fine.  It's just too much for a smaller power bank.So in summary it works well, the price ($40 at time of purchase) is competitive with other similar products, and if I needed another I would start looking at UTechSmart first.

author: RTC
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 19, 2021
content: 7/16/21 purchase date review & 2 month follow-up update that follows:I don't know what to think of this thing. I followed the included connection instructions and it did not do what it advertised, for me. "Plug peripherals into unit. Plug power source into unit. Plug unit into your device." At that point, i expect to see the led light on the unit to come on, have the ability to access any/all connected peripherals, and enjoy the unit I just spent my hard earned money on.That was not my case. The "led powered light" never came on, first of all, so i disconnected everything and reconnected everything in the order the instructions specified many times and the results were 1. I either had Ethernet access with no power distribution or 2. The exact opposite. Never both simultaneously, which it is supposed to do. I, also, tried several different connecting orders, same results. I tried said combo arrangements with several different charging cables and wall chargers to make sure i was getting adequate power delivery to the unit to be able to distribute. Same results. I turned to Amazon technical support, which was a mistake, as trying to explain what was happening and what i tried to do to correct the issue only confused them more and more. Frustrated, i requested an exchange. Upon receiving the replacement, I followed the same procedures with mixed but similar results. Sometimes it would work correctly, sometimes not.I'll chance the possibility that I may be doing something incorrect on my end. That's only fair. But, so far, I'm a bit frustrated with this. I expected to purchase and enjoy the ease of plug and play and go about my business as a satisfied customer. But that seems to be rare results with these Chinese Amazon products regardless of any review, good or bad because i always seem to be the one to be on this end of the stick.I will reserve judgement with a 2 star rating and hope that the seller can contact me with better instructions on how to make this thing work properly. Contacting UTECH support was equally useless. If the seller does contact me and my situation improves, i will return with a better review. Until then, i stand here. Unsatisfied and frustrated that i spent my money on this to get the results I've gotten and wasted my valuable time with all attempts to correct issues. This is not what i had in mind.9/12/21 2 month update:The unit continued to work only intermittently, until it finally stopped working altogether. Educated guess, both had faulty power ports. What are the odds of 2 units, back to back, having the same issue? The unit is, now, past the return window so I am forced to eat the $30 purchase price, including the headache over the whole matter. The seller never contacted me, as requested. Highly disappointed, to say the least.For the majority, it appears the unit has worked out well. Lucky them. But for me... Not so. 2 strikes and I was out. I worked hard for that money and with inflation as it is and the cost of everything rising, spending my hard earned money on leisurely items is not something that I do much of these days and had to budget wisely in order to cover the purchase price.If you purchase this unit, odds are in your favor for a solid product. As for me, I think I will save and spend a few more dollars and purchase name brand, American built, products (if there is such a thing these days).All I can say is, Good luck to you. I hope it works out. My days off buying cheap Chinese brands to save a dollar are over.... And never will I purchase from this seller again. You had 2 months to contact me guys! What happened to taking care of your customer after the sale?If I could rate 0 stars, I would.

author: Bob S
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 4, 2024
content: My new HP laptop has one Type A and one Type C connection. This added 3 high speed USB type A connections and has a Type C connector to replace the one needed to connect to the laptop. The best thing is, though my new laptop has no wired Ethernet port this dongle added a Gig Ethernet port.  Be patient it took about 30 seconds to be recognized but once it was I got full speed internet. Though the laptop does have wireless Ethernet, with my internet provider modem/router wireless is half speed of wired. No configuration needed and It is set for DHCP out of the box. Very happy.Bad news, and not advertised, is not all Type C ports support HDMI (or any other) video and my HP laptop is one that doesn't. So no HDMI out. However this not the dongle's issue but the laptop's and I am very happy with the rest of the performance. Would buy again.

author: Bryan in Orlando
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 7, 2023
content: As of May 2023:I have a 2020 MacBook Air. At first, this hub worked perfectly, and I only needed to use one MacBook USB-C port for everything, including power. After a few months of use, the power stopped working. As it stands right now, the power might work fine after initially connecting it, but it will not work after a reboot. I was hoping to keep the hub in a cable management box, but I don't want to have to keep taking it out to fiddle with the power cord.Overall, I'm happy with the hub. I just wish the power port worked consistently.Updated 9/24/2023:The power port seems to work better now, but the USB 3.0 connections now won't work for a mouse and keyboard. I've tried on my MacBook and HP laptop, and rebooted both. Nothing. I'm changing my review to one star.

author: Moses
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 5, 2022
content: This seems like a very attractive and useful product, but it just did not last for me.  I bought it in August 2021 and used it daily for an ethernet connection with intermittent use as a USB hub.  Within 6 months I started to have mysterious connectivity issues, but for some reason always found a way to blame my internet provider somehow.  But then the dropped Zoom calls got to be just too much and I decided to go through my whole system replacing one part at a time. My problem was cured (and remains cured for 2 months) after replacing the first connection in the sequence - this device.  It also used to get very warm when in use, and I have the impression that it got warmer when any USB plug was used and that was associated with more ethernet failure. USB functionality was also a little weird and selective - things like keyboards worked fine, camera memory card readers very selective.

author: Frank Beeck
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 6, 2023
content: This device randomly brings down my whole (wired) Netgear Home Gigabit Network. The network had been working stable for years. Once disconnecting this USB C Hub from the computer, it wrecks the whole home network. The LED at the hub start blinking almost solid and no other device connected to the network works anymore. The moment I disconnect the hub, everything starts working again. It happens every day or every other day. I'm disappointed in the device :-(What I've learnt from this experience is, that the current generation of USB C Hub's differ in technology and are either "Full USB-C" based or are "Thunderbolt 3" based. The vendor of the replacement Hub that I ordered instead clarified this little but significant aspect upfront. It would have been nice if UtechSmart had done the same. It would have saved me a lot of trouble.I returned the UtechSmart USB-C device and UtechSmart offered a full refund.

author: Nicolas-Cyril Namar
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 29, 2022
content: When I have my computer plugged into the hub, Ethernet works as expected, and the network activity light only flashes when there's network activity. The adapter starts acting up when I unplug my computer from the hub. Once unplugged, the hub's (and Ethernet switch's) activity light starts flashing indefinitely. And all wired devices plugged into the network lose connection. Essentially, this hub crashes my network when my computer's not plugged into it.My intent is to keep the hub plugged into Ethernet, power, and a display at at all times, and simply plug my computer in with the USB-C cable. You know-- like a hub's intended. If I have to unplug the Ethernet cable from the hub, it kind of defeats the purpose.Also, I can't help but be suspicious of the fact that the hub was having any network activity whatsoever with nothing plugged into it...

author: Andrew Miner
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 29, 2021
content: Do NOT buy this junk, you are wasting your money. I purchased this when I got a new slimmer laptop without an ethernet port.The first USB hub I received worked for about a day with a 65W laptop charger and an ethernet port connected. It started to smoke, smelled like burning, and got extremely hot the second day I had it. It stopped functioning, and was unusable. I contacted the seller and they agreed to send me a replacement.Upon receiving the replacement, it also started smoking and smelling like burning, just within hours of starting to use it, also becoming unusable.Originally the seller asked me to return it within an allotted time (30 days) for a full refund of the first unit, however I decided to take the first one apart and see if I could find any noticeable damage. The small chip labeled C64 has melted and has caused some burned marks on itself and a few caps around it.So now, i'm $60 in, I don't have a working HUB, and this thing is a piece of junk. Buy something else.

author: David Anthony Nedved
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2022
content: This was a frustrating product. Tried using as the central component (hub if you will) of my Macbook Pro desktop setup. From the initial usage it was flaky, requiring multiple plug/un-plug cycles to get everything to work at the same time. 2/3 times the video would not work, maybe 1/4 times the USB would not work. Ended up taking an average of 4 or 5 times to plug in and remove to get everything working. Then after several months of this the power pass-through stopped working. I found out when I walked up to my device I had left plugged in and the battery was dead. Now it sort of works when I power through the other USB port but not when I try to pass power through. A few weeks after this the laptop's USB ports failed, I can't say what caused it of course but reading other reviews who also had their ports fail it does make me wonder. I replaced the laptop, now I guess I'll try again to get a working docking station but won't trust this brand again!

author: Marvin
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 24, 2022
content: Edit: my network started seeing some issues shortly after getting this. When plugged into Ethernet, it crashes my network switch. Once rebooted, the switch works fine, but it takes down my entire network because my Wi-Fi APs are also plugged into this switch.Risky buy!! Hence the 1 star.This works great on our 2021 MacBook Pro 16" M1, however a driver had to be downloaded directly from the Asix website to get Ethernet working. It was not plug and play. The adapter is the AX88179 chip, we are running MacOS Monterey 12.6 and got it working by following the driver install directions.Other than that, this dock has eliminated so many cables from our plug-n-play desk setup now, meaning only one cable has to be plugged into the Mac for power, data, and networking. Such a great value!

content: This hub seriously sucks. Even when I need it to do the bare minimum it can't handle it. author: dylan ham
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 12, 2020
content:
The media could not be loaded.
                



Returned this product because the HDMI goes crazy. Tried with other monitors and other cables and other ports on my same laptop and other USB C hubs - the problem is definitely this device. My monitor randomly wakes up and goes to sleep and won't stay off when my computer is supposed to have the screen off. Also the screen randomly goes black and for a second and comes back on. And worst yet, after using for about 10 minutes or so, the screen is cut into left and right halves at a random place and those two halves are swapped (as crazy as it sounds) and stays that way until I unplug the HDMI and plug it back in. (Not sure how that's even possible.) Ordered two of them and they both have the same problems although one fails a lot faster than the other.  (My device: Google Pixelbook.)

author: NotAZombie
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 5, 2022
content: The good: USB, ethernet, and charging all work as advertised. If you don't care about display out, this will do you fine.The bad: Only 30 Hz regardless of resolution. I've tried 1080P, 4K, various ultrawide configs, 720p, and others. Only ever able to get 30 Hz. In addition, this adds probably 200ms of lag. What that means practically is that you move your mouse, and it takes a fraction of a second for you to see that movement show up on screen. This may not sound like a big deal, but I found myself overshooting where I wanted to click or mistyping and backspacing too far, or audio and video being out of sync. It's just horrible.

date: Reviewed in the United States on November 5, 2018
content: Previous review: So awesome. Replaces your OTG cable completely and does so much more. Best buy I've had in a long time! Makes it easy to connect to a TV or video game pad or flash drive to off load your videos and pictures. What can I say. It's very awesome. Oh and it's heavy duty!! Solid!**Update**There is a major flaw I've discovered in this. Unless I got a dud. It's the USB C charging part. The part where you are supposed to keep your device charged doesn't charge at all. It will bring up the indicator saying it's charging but your battery quickly depletes.So I had to take away 2 stars for that. Basically you can use this but your device will die soon each time.I would give it a few stars still but the sellers did NOT even reach out to replace it or show concern for their product! At least stand by your product! Since they did not I must change to 1 star.

content: Hooked everything up and it appeared to all be working fine. author: Gary R Holland
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 21, 2021
content: I have to use a product like this because my laptop does not have an ethernet port and I can only connect to the internet via a wired connection at this moment.  I was sitting in bed with this plugged into my laptop and smoke started coming out of the HDMI port.  I'm glad I caught this as soon as I did because something like this is no joke with how many things could go wrong in that situation.  I only had the ethernet port taken up at the time, so I could not imagine what this thing would do if I were using multiple ports at once.  I do not think this product is worth burning your leg or possibly worse, so I would not recommend this to anyone.

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 13, 2022
content: Bought this UtechSmart 6 In 1 USB C hub over a year ago for my daughter's 13-inch laptop.  I recently noticed that she wasn't using her 24" desk monitor with the laptop.  She had thought the HDMI cable was bad.  Being the engineer that I am, I began troubleshooting and confirmed the issue was not the HDMI cable but was this USB hub.  The UtechSmart USB C HDMI and USB ports are no longer functional.  My daughter is temporarily using my USB-C hub from another manufacturer which works just fine.  Looks like I'll be sticking with the higher quality USB C hubs from now on.

author: MarshallOT614
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 7, 2021
content: I bought this mainly for Ethernet functionality on my work MacBook Pro, as I've been using a different adapter just for HDMI for years, but I'm in need of a more stable network connection. I can hear clicking noises in the device whenever traffic goes over the wire, and it's loud enough that it's annoying. Watching video or downloading large files makes the thing go crazy. It literally sounds like I'm hearing packets, which is kind of cool, but also worrying. To make things worse, my monitor keeps on randomly turning off, and I'm hearing sparking sounds when I adjust the HDMI cable. This thing is either going to catch fire or destroy something it's connected to.

content: I bought this to have a single USB C connection for my laptop so that I don't need to connect my USB Mouse, External Hard Disks, and Second Monitor each with separate cables. author: LT
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 5, 2022
content: This is the first time I have ever had an adapter break so quickly.  Usually, you should get years of use out of an adapter, but this time, I was surprised that the adapter broke after 3 months.  I plugged it into my laptop this morning and none of my devices were recognized.  Took some troubleshooting on my part and then noticed that it was the adapter that was broken.  Extremely disappointed at the short lifespan of this product.  Originally, it did the trick.  It's light enough and portable but just doesn't last.

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 17, 2024
content: I bought this for my Dell Inspiron 7000 after I got gigabit Internet service. My laptop did not have an Ethernet port, only USB-C and I didn't want to dedicate the only USB-C port to an RJ45 adapter. So I bought this device. Unfortunately, the USB-C port doesn't work for anything I can discover. It won't charge my phone and I can't open my phone on my laptop. Also, I connected a second monitor into the HDMI port but the monitor's image didn't scale correctly. The image was slightly too big for the physical screen. I tried adjust scaling, resolution, etc., to no avail. I wrote the  seller's tech support, but they never got back to me. So I'm returning it and buying the Amazon USB-C to RJ45 adapter for half the price.

author: Dylan
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 12, 2024
content: I have transitioned to using much less of the ports on this product; from using all of the HDMI’s, USB, and Ethernet to just running one HDMI and one USB off of this. This is because every single issue I’ve faced with my devices has been solved simply from switching away from this particular hub. I’ve had this product about 2 months and can say that if you’re looking for something that will consistently work for your needs, please put in the extra few dollars and find another product. Issues I face with this product is lagging on my second monitor, random disconnects due to the cheap build of the device and even software issues that causes more cleanup on my end. The biggest issue is that it’s cheap hardware. Don’t take after me- if you’re already spending the money for one its probably because you need it (and need it to work for that matter too) and this is not that product for you.

author: AllenG
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 9, 2023
content: I use this adaptor for ethernet, HDMI output, USB-C charging, & a Logitec USB-A wireless mouse and keyboard.  I have purchased and use 2 of these adaptors.  When charging my new Dell XPS13 through this adapter with its USB-C power cable, my computer reports that I am using a low power charging cable and to use the cable that came with the computer, which I am already using.  My computer says that it is "slow charging".  This adaptor is listed as "100W power delivery" and my computer uses a 45W power cable, so I thought that a 100W capacity would easily handle it.  The USB wireless mouse and keyboard work with intermittent disruptions through any of this adaptor's USB-A ports but work fine when plugged in via the other USB-C port on the computer using a simple USB-C to USB-A adaptor.  I purchased my two adaptors 3-years apart and they both yield the same results on my new XPS 13.  My prior XPS 13 did not use the USB-C charging, but it exhibited the same problem when using the adaptor for my wireless mouse/keyboard, which is quickly annoying.  This wasn't a big issue when using my prior computer because it had built-in USB-A ports that I could use.  The ethernet and HDMI seem to work fine on this adaptor.

content: Didn't work with my MacBook Air (M2). The OS sees the devices (keyboard, monitor, mouse) and even identifies them in the OS, but no control or video signal is sent/received. Hopefully people with Windows OS will have better luck.

author: BH
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 4, 2022
content: If you're hoping to add some extras to a new Dell laptop, you may want to take a look at what's compatible. Dell doesn't allow 3rd party hardware to preform PD, you may use a 3rd party USB-C charger of appropriate wattage directly but geniuses at Dell restrict Power delivery unless the thunderbolt port detects Dell OEM parts.I bought a 95w USB-C Charger to connect Power Delievery through 3 seperate USB-C port(usb3.0)/rj45/HDMI devices that all claim to have Battery PD (including this one), but the Battery keeps saying the charger is slow. over hours the battery will trickly down to about 95% before I plug it back into the OEM charger it came with. I did some looking around and Dell is as Dell Does. Dell is notorious for being OEM specific, they are the Apple of the PC world. Most Dell models WILL NOT do PD unless you buy a USB-C/Thunderbolt 3 dock/adapter and Charger that are both OEM. So keep that in mind. Silver lining is that is the charger is directly connected to the USB-C, It works, I just don't have the extra 3 USB 3.1/1 USB-C/RJ45/HDMI that would have made my desktop arrangement more manageable... the search continues...

author: DeeJay
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 26, 2022
content: This worked very well for a few weeks with my M1 MacBook Air. After the first few weeks, it got a bit buggy. By that, I mean that sometimes the NIC wouldn't work, or the charging pass-thru wouldn't work, or the USB-C ports wouldn't work...not all at the same time, and only intermittently. Generally, unplugging it an plugging it back in would take care of the issue. Then it became less intermittent and more of a daily occurrence. Then simply unplugging/replugging wouldn't resolve the issue. Finally, after about 6 months, it stopped working entirely. On my MacBook, the NIC showed connected, but I couldn't get online, the USB ports were available, but nothing would connect, and the battery would say it was plugged in, but it wouldn't charge. There was no dramatic, "oh, it's broken" moment but...it ended up in the trash can.

author: Emma A
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 8, 2023
content: On the plus side, it did work for me to connect my mac book pro (only USB C connectors) to the HDMI projector in our conference room. On the minus side, the display came through with a purple cast. It wasn't the projector - other folks who connected directly to HDMI had a clear display with no color issues. We tested the connector with two different macs - both had a color issues with this connector.  We were able to do our meeting but it was annoying. I think you get what you pay for with this connector, and I'll have to find a different one for next time.

author: George Gilman
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 16, 2023
content: Normal operation, it does exactly what it should. However, I routinely bluescreen on my Windows laptop if this is plugged in. Very obvious cause and effect because if this is in, I'm guaranteed to bluescreen within 24 hours. If it is not plugged in, I go months without bluescreening. Whether it doesn't like my monitor, network connection, or whatever... I can't say but there's something in my system that it clearly doesn't like and behaves poorly because of it. I'd probably give it at least 4 stars if it didn't routinely cause me to bluescreen.

content: (UPDATE BELOW!) The USB ports stopped working after 3 months. author: Christina Sarlo
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 8, 2020
content: I purchased this item for use in school as I am a virtual teacher. I recently was upgraded to a 2020 MacBook Air which does not have standard USB-A ports. I needed this adapter in order to be able to use my wireless mouse and other regular USB-A accessories. When using this adapter, my wireless mouse was so laggy that it could not even be used. This was not the case when I used other adapters with my wireless mouse. Second, my MacBook air would not charge at all through this adapter. I was Zooming and noticed that my MacBook was about to die while my charger was plugged into the adapter. What's the point? I couldn't use it to charge my Mac and I couldn't use it with my wireless mouse either. At this point, this adapter was very useless to me and was very disappointing.

date: Reviewed in the United States on June 16, 2022
content: Generally, it does what you want in a hub. For some reason, I am seeing latency with my wireless mouse (I tried two and had the same problem with both). The problem occurs with all three ports. Basically, there is a delay in the cursor moving on the screen and sometimes it jumps arround sporatically. Occasionally, it stops responding altogether. I ended up plugging the mouse directly into my computer. Would suggest this hub if you have a bluetooth mouse or plan to connect it directly to your computer, but otherwise it doesn't quite work as desired.

content: Was not expecting to write a review about this product, but I has to let others know some of the problems I have encountered that are all related to the product. First! I wish I could send it back for a refund or in exchange for another unit to see if it's better.

author: Dave
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 16, 2023
content: In June 2023 the HDMI port of a unit I ordered in Oct 2021 gave out, and its power port stopped working not long after that. I decided 30$ for 17 months wasn't a terrible price and gave this as a 4star review noting these details.In Sep 2023 the power port of the replacement unit I got in June gave out. So that one lasted only 3 months, which is a big difference from the 17 months the first unit lasted, or an average of 10 months life cycle.I already have a third unit in hand that I ordered it in August just in case this very situation was going to happen. So I've updated this review and lowered from 4 to 2 stars because at an average of 10months life, the effective actual cost of this unit would be ~65$ a year. Now I might have to find another manufacturer; we will see how the third unit does. I work from home and can't afford to have this inconvenience unexpectedly.Another update: In Jan 2024 the last unit's HDMI and power ports failed. Now the average lifespan of the 3 failed units is down to 8 months (17mo for one, 3mo and 5mo). So I've swapped in the third "spare" unit while ordering another new one.. for which I will send back the bad one. I tried to contact the company to no avail. These units are great until they fail, and since I'm keeping myself resupplied without extra cost (except the hassle of driving somewhere to return them) to supplant the inability to get customer support, I'm changing from 2 to 3 stars. Hopefully I can get the average to 18+ months, at which point I would be satisfied.

content: My UtechSmart 6-in-1 USB C Hub died peacefully in its sleep last night after just over three and a half years of dedicated, nearly daily service, each year of which earned it a star that now adorns this review in memoriam. author: Harald Hardrada
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 19, 2022
content: If you only plug this device in at night to charge, it will probably last 2+ years and serve you well. If you use it like a docking station, i.e. connecting and disconnecting as you come and go from the office, it will wear out much faster.  Mine started to have difficulty connecting to my phone after 6 months, and at one year I have to plug it in several times to get it to connect. It also drops the connection at random.The other weakness it's had from day one is that the gigbit ethernet interface takes a lot of power. When using it to browse, the time it takes to charge from 15% increases from 2-3 hours to 10-30 hours (even with the factory charger that supports USB Power Delivery). Heavy use will drain the battery even when it's plugged in.Neither of these problems are the fault of the manufacturer or their engineers. USB-C just isn't as tough as USB-A or the ports on a good quality laptop docking station. And most gigabit ethernet devices consume much more power than their 10/100 predecessors.If those are acceptable limitations, then by all means by this product. It's as well-made as it could be given the limitations of the industry standards.

author: Tyler
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 5, 2021
content: I have owned this type c dongle for about 2 years it has been great! but do use an HP Spectre from 2018 and the power drain when the laptop is off is insane! leave your laptop off for more than 6 hours or for like a day expect your battery to be gone!I have also used this with Samsung Dex with my S9+ and it been great, but there's a problem. When you have the dongle connected into the phone, and your already in DEX mode and your power is draining you go to plug in power into it, it completely reboots DEX mode, and acts as tho you unplugged it from the device and plugged it back in.With Windows this same behavior that happened with Samsung Dex that happens on the windows side is different and I have had my external monitors freak out before a few times, I have once had all the ports filled up and doing a data transfer I saw I needed to plug in my HP Spectre Laptop and it then completely blue screened my laptop resetting and messing up what I had been working on.Overall it's a useful dongle it's a nice metal, feel and style but has little hiccups with software and power consumption that are pretty wacky.

content: I have been using it at work for a year.  I purchased end of 2021 (Nov). author: sarahjw19
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2023
content: This hub is really quite something. It was plugged in to a laptop to use Ethernet on a device that did not have a port (what we bought it for) for 24hours and all of a sudden there’s 30 devices connected to our network all through Ethernet connection which is impossible. We replaced the router and modem and had the same problem 24 hours later. I have no idea why this happened but it freaked me out. Spectrum at first thought our internet was getting attacked. Turns out it’s this hub we bought off Amazon. Anyone else have this issue? I mean… it works I guess. But WHY did it do this?!

content: I have a new Dell laptop, running Windows 10, with only USB-C ports.  It came with a little USB-C fan out adapter dongle that has an HDMI and a USB-A port. My wireless Logitech mouse and keyboard, with the little USB wireless adapter, work perfectly with the original fan out adapter, but with this device the mouse is "jumpy" and the keyboard is intermittent. date: Reviewed in the United States on June 22, 2020
content: Well, i really wanted to like this hub, and for most parts its not bad.I got it for 2 reason to have Ethernet and HDMI so i can use external monitor.Ethernet works fine, at least i didn't see any issues with it yet. HDMI on other hand is a big issue, I keep loosing video signal every 15-20 seconds, and when it comes back, there is overscan,and display pictured is  shifted right by about and 1.5" and then wraps around to left. I tried 3 different power adapters with viruses power options and different HTMI cables to no avail.Edit: I got replacement hub, and increased my rating to 3* from 1*, HDMI Flicker is almost gone now, but i also had to turn of Auto Signal Detect on the Monitor, witch means to bring monitor out of sleep i need to cycle the sources.Also once a while Ethernet gets stock, and i need to "reboot" the Hub by disconnecting it from everything...

content: After a few hours of operation with HDMI, Ethernet and USB connected, this unit overheated.  Since it has a metal case, I fixed it by putting it on top of a metal block that I happen to have on my desk, which dissipated enough heat that it went back to working normally.I think all of these units use the same chipset since they all seem show the same symptoms when they overheat (some of the ports repeatedly disconnect and reconnect).Apart from that, the unit works fine.  Just don't believe the claims about better thermal design.

author: Bill Sheppard
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 16, 2020
content: This is one of the lower-priced USB-C hubs and all the ports work consistently. I have found, however, that it does not work well with a wireless keyboard dongle due to poor shielding. After much experimentation I've found that the keyboard dongle (I'm using Logitech, but I imagine most would see the same issue) must be plugged into the HDMI-side USB port. If I plug it into the other side the keyboard works very erratically. When plugged into the HDMI-side the keyboard will work fine within 2-3 feet of the dongle, but not from further than that. I tried plugging the dongle into two other USB-C hubs and the keyboard worked reliably from 10+ feet away (as the keyboard spec promises).So if you won't be using this with a wireless keyboard dongle (or presumably other wireless dongles) the hub is great. But for wireless use it's not ideal and potentially won't work, depending on your use case.

author: Sue H.
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 17, 2019
content: I use this as a docking station at home.  HDMI to monitor, mouse, headset, and ethernet.  It works just fine.two things.  #1 I wish the cord was longer, it's only 6" or so.  But I bought a 3 foot extension cable and it still works just fine.  #2 when I unplug my laptop, I can still see the ethernet lights flashing, which means it;s consuming power.  I think if the laptop is unplugged it should switch off.  Other than those two small items, it works!UPDATE:  I just upgraded my internet to 400Mbps download, and this device can't handle that over the wired gigabit ethernet port.  When I connect ethernet to this device, the max I get is about 200Mbps plus or minus.  When I connect ethernet to the port directly on my laptop I get 450Mbps.  Clearly this device can not handle high speed ethernet.

date: Reviewed in the United States on April 25, 2019
content: This thing caused headaches since the day it arrived. First, I had to purchase a power adapter because this device draws power from my laptop and caused a battery warning light to come on. The product page did not mention anything about providing power to the unit - there was one picture depicting the device connected to the wall but no written instructions explaining that the hub needs power. Once powered and connected, the device worked fine, until the Ethernet stopped working (that is why I purchased the hub). I talked with support and returned the item because it was defective. The Ethernet worked for a couple of days on the new hub, until it stopped working again. I will be returning the item for the last time and will purchase another hub from a different manufacturer.

author: Scott
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 28, 2020
content: This is an effective product to add functionality to my Surface Pro 7. I have a Kensington case for the computer because I take it into the field occasionally, and this works with the case on without a problem. I have seen other options that plug in to both the USB-A (regular USB) and USB-C (phone-charger-style USB) ports to give USB-C passthrough functionality, but those wouldn't work with my case. I use the HDMI port daily for a second monitor, and I use the ethernet port periodically if I have to uplink in one of our offices. Both ports seem to work without fail. The fact that each USB port on here is USB 3.0 is a huge selling point. The only thing I haven't used on this device is the power-delivery USB-C port, but I'm sure it would work just fine if I tried. The unit is aluminum but feels sturdy without being heavy.There is one concern with this device for me, and that's the cord. It is about 4 inches long from device to plug, and the device itself is another 4-ish inches. The port is 6" from the bottom of the computer. As a result, the device doesn't sit flat on the desktop, but rather at somewhat of an angle, and I believe that causes strain at the port plug. If the cord were just two, maybe three inches longer, the device would sit flat without any concern. Obviously this concern applies only to tablet-style or 2-in-1 computers, because laptops have their ports flush with the desk. But for me, it drops a star because it's unnecessary stress at the port, which could eventually wear out the connection. (That's supposedly not an issue for USB-C, but I'm skeptical.)Overall, best purchase for the money for my purposes. Would buy again, even with the 4 inch cord.

author: Bob S
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 4, 2024
content: My new HP laptop has one Type A and one Type C connection. This added 3 high speed USB type A connections and has a Type C connector to replace the one needed to connect to the laptop. The best thing is, though my new laptop has no wired Ethernet port this dongle added a Gig Ethernet port.  Be patient it took about 30 seconds to be recognized but once it was I got full speed internet. Though the laptop does have wireless Ethernet, with my internet provider modem/router wireless is half speed of wired. No configuration needed and It is set for DHCP out of the box. Very happy.Bad news, and not advertised, is not all Type C ports support HDMI (or any other) video and my HP laptop is one that doesn't. So no HDMI out. However this not the dongle's issue but the laptop's and I am very happy with the rest of the performance. Would buy again.

author: Kitsap Consumer
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 21, 2022
content: I had tried two other highly recommended USB C hubs but I could not get either to work as an Ethernet adapter with google Chromecast with Google TV.  This USB C hub worked perfectly as an Ethernet adapter for Google TV so this is the first hub that I have been able to test as an additional storage hub.  I also wanted this hub to increase the storage capacity of my Chromecast with Google TV. However, despite using a 65W power supply for the hub, I could not see any of the attached USB flash drives. I tried multiple formats including Fat32, drives with only a few files and drives from 32 to 128 GB, but this did not seem to make a difference.  All of the flash drives could be read if I plugged them directly into the USB 2.0 port on my Samsung TV. This USB C hub also worked when plugged into a desktop computer. I did some more research and I ran across warnings from Samsung that a USB hub should not be used in the TV USB ports, with no indication why. It appears that most people who are using a USB C hub to increase storage for Google TV have newer vintage TVs than mine, and their TV is not a Samsung. My Samsung Smart TV is 11 years old and like most older Smart TVs it is becoming progressively Dumb, as apps are removed and new ones cannot be added. In fact, I added the Google for TV to this TV so that I would have access to apps that could not be downloaded. After 2 failures to find a hub that worked as an Ethernet adapter, and this hub worked as an Ethernet adapter but not to add storage, I now suspect that it is the Samsung TV that cannot read the attached flash drives in a hub through the Google device. So I can't use this hub if the TV will not recognize it, and I'll just get a Google branded Ethernet adapter. As long as the TV continues to work, I see no reason to buy a new TV and I'll just continue to work within the limited storage on the Google for TV device. Clearly it would be much better if Smart TVs did not become Dumb TVs, and if streaming devices actually included a reasonable amount of storage or you could add storage without having to add third party devices.

date: Reviewed in the United States on May 3, 2022
content: I was looking for an USB C Ethernet adapter for my new Samsung Galaxy book 2 Pro 360, and the first couple I ordered had the problem of constantly disconnecting and reconnecting. After some digging into the issue, it seems this has been a common problem the plagues USB C adapters, and may be due to the connection being loose, or the hub overheating, and the hub not being able to supply all the power necessary to maintain connection. So I needed a hub that had PD so that power draw would always be sufficient to maintain connection. This hub has worked as advertised, It hasn't disconnected once, and I have plugged 3 external hard drives, in addition to the Ethernet port, and getting very fast speeds, well over 400 Mbps on my 400 Mbps plan, and upload speeds are as advertised as well. So far I am very happy with the purchase, I will update this review once I have used the HDMI port.Update: 7.15.22My laptop no longer recognizes the USB Hub. I contacted customer service to request a warranty replacement, and they shipped one out within a couple days. After sthinking about why the first hub failed, I believe it could be a heat issue. I have 3 external USB SSDs connected to the hub along with the Ethernet port, and the USB C power delivery port to provide the necessary power. I notice it gets quite warm, so I have been monitoring the heat, and placing it on a cooling pad, which keeps it from getting too hot. I wish I didn't have to use the cooling pad, but I'm pretty sure that was what led to the other hub failing.

date: Reviewed in the United States on August 19, 2022
content: I use a Macbook for work.  Apple has decided to only use usb C (for better or worse).  So I bought one of these hubs so I could attach other non usb c devices and a monitor.  If you need just a basic hub / docking station these aren't a bad choice.  Reasonably priced and will get the job done.  I haven't tried to do any large file transfers or have done anything outside of typical office work use.  I was happy enough with this product to get a second one so I could attach a second monitor to my macbook.My biggest complaint would be quality control.  The second hub I purchased, if I lock my screen and then log back in at a later time the monitor doesn't reconnect.  I have to unplug the HDMI cable and plug it back in to get the screen to come back one.  This doesn't happen with the first hub I purchased.  I have flip flopped the monitors between the 2 hubs to see if it was just an issue with connected monitor.  I have used different USB C ports on my Macbook.  I have used the 2nd hub just stand alone.  The issue only occurs with the second hub I purchased in any configuration I've tried.  So I guess this would be a quality control issue.  Not the biggest problem, just annoying.

content: It expands the connectivity options of my Windows OS laptop that only has one USB C port.  The USB C port on the hub does have limited functionality over the port on the laptop, so I can't use it like I had hoped to, but the documentation and included information all warned of that limitation. I did not do that often enough for this to be a major problem.  Previously I had the second monitor occupying the USB C port 24/7, I now have more options with the hub in place.)

author: Tomvision
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 17, 2018
content: I'm using this hub with a 12" Retina Macbook (early 2016) with the single USB-C port. I bought the official OEM Digital AV Multiport Adapter when I got the MacBook, but it only has one USB-A port and I needed a minimum of 2. I bought this hub because it was the most recent one added on Amazon at the time, meaning it should have the latest technology in it. Here's what I've discovered using it. Hopefully this will be helpful to someone:• With a USB 3.1 Samsung T3 SSD connected to the hub with the correct USB cable, I get ~380 MB/sec write, ~420 MB/sec read. So don't worry, you really will get USB 3 speeds with this hub.• Your total USB power budget is about 1A across all three USB-A ports. That's not 1A per port, that's 1A TOTAL (1A/3=333mA per USB port). That's all you get, and that power is all coming from the single USB-C port on the MacBook so forget plugging in a bunch of self-powered USB hard drives. Oh and don't think you'll be clever and plug in the MacBook's USB-C charger for more power--that won't work. More on that in a moment.• I successfully connected the Samsung T3 SSD (roughly 600-700mA power draw), an Android phone (charging at 300mA, verified using the Ampere app), and a keyboard (100mA). In this configuration, I tried copying files between the Samsung SSD and the MacBook and the Android phone and the MacBook (both copies going simultaneously) and it worked fine.• I couldn't plug in the Samsung T3 SSD and a SanDisk 32GB USB 3.0 flash drive at the same time. Once I tried to copy files from one to the other, the copy would hang in the Finder for about 15-20 secs, then the Samsung would unmount. The two devices combined most likely exceeded the hub's 900mA/1A power budget.• I was able to plug in two SanDisk USB 3.0 flash drives and copy files between them. So, I'm betting their combined current draw was less than 1A. A third one probably wouldn't have worked.• The Power Delivery feature doesn't actually power anything connected to the hub. It's solely there to provide power to the MacBook. There's no difference using the hub with the USB-C power input connected and not using it, other than the laptop charges. Again, it won't get you more power to run more stuff off the hub's USB-A ports.• I connected a Logitech M557 Bluetooth mouse and it seemed to work OK while the hub was connected.• I didn't test the Ethernet port. According to System Information it is still drawing power, possibly 200mA or so.• This hub uses a VIA chipset, possibly the VL817. This is reported by the System Information app on the Mac.So, bottom line is it gives me my much needed second USB port, even though I'm sorta on thin ice with the power draw. If you have hard drives that have their own power supplies (meaning they plug into a power strip), then you'll most likely be OK with this hub.

author: DPC rates
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 11, 2020
content:
The media could not be loaded.
                



I am using this product every day and it has been working.  I intend to keep using it and I would recommend it. But there are 5 minor things I experienced when using with a current model Catalina MacBook Pro.  I will document them in a quick video too:1.  it gets really hot.  This is typical of products that heat sink to the outer chassis, especially if it is metal and especially if you have all ports populated with active USB electronics.2. The connector is hard to withdraw from the USBC port because it fits tight and the handle is totally smooth.  Finger grips or surface knurls would make it much easier to unplug it.3.  When I use the HDMI output, for some reason my computer sees it as a DisplayPort device.  This hasn't caused any problems yet, but HDMI and DisplayPort EDID codes are not the same, so I can see situations where it could be an issue.4.  Every so often the audio over the HDMI output will not work.  I have been unable to track this problem to my computer or my TV since they work independently and with every other scenario I have tried.  So it must be the hub.  If I put the computer to sleep, the problem will be fixed when I wake it back up.5.  When the computer is shut down, sometimes the power light on my webcam will flicker.  This shouldn't really be happening since the power supply input is strictly for charging the computer and shouldn't be powering anything else.  So far it has not caused issues, but it worries me a little.It is worth the money, good size, good construction, so far I am happy with it.THANKS!

author: AmazonD
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 22, 2019
content: I ordered this so I would not have 3 separate dongles for my devices. It has a solid well built feel to it but it has some issues. It is usable but not great. An unexperienced user would have a hard time using this device.1. I have tried several different wireless mouse usb dongles (2.4) in the usb ports (Logitech,MS,Dell,Lenovo) and none of them work but my other dongles do not have this issue with wireless mouse connections.2. I use the hdmi connector with an LG ULTRAWIDE(34UC79G) with the first boot in the morning I will usually have to unplug the hdmi cable and plug it back into the dongle to force a handshake to get my mac to detect the monitor.3  I am on a 2017 15" Macbookpro running the latest update of Mojave and if the dongle is plugged in during boot the is a long delay before the keyboard is detected. If you need to use the keyboard for logging in I suggest waiting until the login screen comes up  and then plugging in the dongle. Everything on it loads faster than if it is plugged in before you turn the Mac on.Update: after I wrote my review I was contacted by Support and found that my unit was defective a new unit was sent out and everything worked good except for the wireless mouse issue.  It turns out that 2.4 ghz wireless dongles are not compatible with usb 3.0 ports.

author: pjkim
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 24, 2022
content: The good:First off, the build quality is good and the aluminum enclosure is a nice touch. The aluminum cover gets slightly warm to the touch which is the point. This was a reasonably priced adapter with USB C power input, HDMI out and gigabit ethernet. The HDMI out works out of the box.The bad (at least on MacOS 12.1 Monterey):The ethernet adapter doesn't work without installing the Realtek drivers. I won't post a link because you should get the latest from realtek.com-- it was 1.0.22 in January 2022. Search for "realtek rtl8153 driver macOS" to find the latest. I read that the "AppleUSBRealtek8153Patcher.kext" needed to be deleted before installing the realtek drivers and spent and inordinate amount of time trying to find out how to delete the SIP protected files-- terminal typin brothers will know the pain, but on Monterey, the usual csrutil disable schtick doesn't work no more! It turns out the realtek drivers seem to work just fine even with the Apple kext still there.

author: AP
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 14, 2019
content: Disclaimer: Don't know too much about computers. Review is based on past experience. Will try to use computery language.I'm currently using the HP x360 Spectre 15" late 2018 model.Positive+ Works well.+ Very light, slim and small.+ No setup required (i.e. driver download).+ Sturdy USB C connector (The part you plug into your computer). Had issues with cheap USB C connectors bending, but this one seems pretty sturdy.+ Ethernet. Had issues with previous hubs not properly recognizing the ethernet cable causing intermittent disconnects, but have not had any issues with this product, YET.+ HDMI. Had no issues supporting my 1440p external monitor. Not sure if necessary information, but my laptop's monitor supports up to 4K resolution.Negatives- Heats up a little bit. Very minor and should be expected I guess.- Cord is very short and inflexible.- Plastic? If you didn't read through the whole product description, you might assume it's made of out steel. They claim "aircraft grade aluminum," but I'm a little skeptical. Not to be offensive, but it does feel a little cheap and fragile. My guess would be that it's mostly plastic with a hint of aluminum. It should be fine, however, if you're not being overly clumsy. Usually, I don't care about the texture, but with this, in consideration, I felt the price was less justified. Would put this product in the late 20 to early 30 dollars range.

author: Yev Z
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 14, 2021
content: I purchased this hub for my 24" iMac with the M1 chip. So if you're using this for a laptop, just disregard my complaint below.Overall, there's nothing wrong with this hub. Although I have not been able to achieve claimed writing and read speeds through its USB 3.0 ports, it's fast enough for my needs.The only issue I have is the main cable that connects it to the computer is too short for an iMac. This means it dangles behind the iMac body and doesn't quite reach the table. I think others have pointed this out. If the cable was just 2 inches longer, it would probably be fine. I'm also pretty sure extending the cable wouldn't hurt laptop users either...Also, I was slightly mistaken because I thought the USB C port on the hub was a multi-directional communication port. Meaning, you could use it to connect USB C devices to communicate with your iMac. However, it's just a pass-through port for charging. Again, something aimed more for laptop users.

author: Bill Lavagnino
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 15, 2018
content: I've already returned this product. A day after arrival, it started saturating my network to the point where SpeedTest results went from 450Mbps download to 7Mbps. In fact, my upload was greater than the download speed, which should never happen! After reverting to my old dongle, everything returned to normal.I attribute this issue to the driver, Usually I can download the driver, install it, and move on. In this case, I went to the vendors web site, found the driver section, found the driver, and clicked on the link. Message on that page was "File not Found". At that point, I contacted Amazon, and returned it. Disappointing overall, as it was an attractive unit and did not overheat, which is the problem I was trying to solve.I'm on a MacBook Pro (13-inch 2017) running macOS Mojave v10.14.1.*******UPDATE**********After my review above, I received an email from the company. They graciously sent me a new hub at no charge, which has worked all day without incident. While I've only tested for a short time, I thought I would match their graciousness by adding two stars to this review. If the hub fails in the near term, I'll come back and add another update.  I'm hoping it continues to work well, because I really like the look and feel of this hub, and it doesn't get as hot as my old hub. We shall see.

author: David Lachance
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 11, 2021
content: This is not my first usb-C hub, but it was the first one with HDMI.  I bought it primarily to use as a docking station so that I could reduce the number of connections to my laptop to just USB-C when at my desk with my external monitor.  While it is working great for me as a USB port expansion and wired Ethernet, it did not work out as a full docking station.  The powered usb-C input I provided did keep the laptop charged through this hub, it did not work well for video.  Every time I reconnected the laptop, I had lots of flicker and occasionally didn't sync with the monitor.  I ended up unplugging the HDMI and reconnecting it.  After the tenth time I gave up and now just use this hub for USB and Ethernet, but not for laptop power of video.I have taken it out for a service call with my laptop and it worked great for USB expansion, ethernet, and HDMI video on-site.  But, I think my expectations for a site visit and a desktop docking station are a bit different...

author: Diana
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 30, 2021
content: My second monitor is plugged in to HDMI and periodically it just goes black for 2-3 seconds. It happens on two computers.  I propped it up thinking that hanging from an elevated spot was a poor connection. It did help but it's a little random. I'm just typing and it's black, then comes back on.  The power is fine on the monitor.  I contacted them without response after receiving a post card encouraging a review.After a covid response many weeks later the customer service explained the power draw based on the accessories I was plugging in was the likely culprit (adding a phone and Bluetooth headset to charge from  the port at the same time).  This mostly solved the problem.  in addition they sent me a a power bank to plug into that was probably $50 retail at no cost to me plus another c-port.  it seemed an excessive amount of compensation for the problem but I was highly satisfied with the experience.

author: Steven D. Hadfield
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 22, 2021
content: I think this a case of just trying to do too much. If you need a 'jack of all trades' for traveling and not everyday use, then I think this is right for you. But do not expect it to work 24x7x365. I have a 65w power supply for my laptop and this tops out at  60w, so part of this is my fault because it burned out - well, art of it did. I got this because I needed power and internet in one device back I only have 2 USB-C ports and I have 3 devices. And I foolishly thought I'd use all of these at the same time, and it work under constant use. So don't expect that. It gets hot when just using wired internet. It did handle internet and power for 7 months. A plus is - might not charge my laptop anymore, but it still works for wired internet, so its still useful to me.

content: Using a Ethernet splitter along with this hub to be able to use the ethernet for my Chromecast with Google TV.  Plugged this hub in and it started working right away. Sure do enjoy it and really missed it when it wasn't functioning.PS: have been using the hub for about 3 months.

content: Works as advertised, plug-and-play with the steam deck. No real complaints here. Only rating 4 stars because sometimes the audio would start to drop in and out, sound bit-crushed, and other such distortions. Happens reliably a few times during a multi-hour play session, so it's not perfect, but I approve of this shortcoming.Just hooked up the proper Steam Deck Dock, and these audio glitches have not continued. So I'm pretty certain it's the unit itself. YMMV for better or worse, but it's also 1/3rd of the price of the proper Dock, so it's worth springing for until you can pick up the real deal. Filled the gap nicely for an entire month.

content: My laptop has a couple of USB-C ports and one legacy USB-A so it is limited in the number of external devices I can connect to it.  With this hub, I can use a larger display, an external keyboard, and a mouse.  At the same time, I can plug in my USB storage devices. author: R.Proctor
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 5, 2020
content: I wanted all the features this product offered for my Dell XP Laptop with Windows 10, but the product description did not make it clear it would work with Windows.  My laptop does have a USB-C port, originally used for the Dell docking station, so it seemed like this could theoretically work on my hardware.  I first tried to plug it in, then turn on the laptop.  All tests showed it worked except the Ethernet port.  I unplugged it and plugged it back in "live", let Windows find a driver (while already on WiFi network), then the Ethernet port began to work and I was able to turn off WiFi and continued on wired Ethernet (more reliable for web conference calls).I use it to free up my USB ports, and get three more, wired Ethernet, and a 2nd monitor.  i knocked it down one star because the dongle gets quite warm though I am not running any significant power through it, I worry about long-term reliability, but so far it has been worth the price.

author: Wayne S. Pelouch
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 27, 2020
content: Overall, I am very happy with the compact USB-C hub and think it is good value and compact.-1 star:The USB-C "charging port" can't be used with a Dell Latitude (7410) as described for a Macbook Pro. That means you need to use 1 of your Dell USB-C ports with an external charger and 1 USB-C port to connect to this hub. The unused hub USB-C charging port does not work with USB-C connection devices, but I suppose it could be used to charge another device (like an iPhone), but I did not test this. The description was not entirely clear on this.+4 star:The Ethernet port works great (tested) and the 3 USB3 ports are very useful. In addition the HDMI port rounds off the connectivity to make it a great travel hub. When I plugged it into my Dell, it worked instantly without any drivers required (as far as I could tell). The construction seems durable and it is very light weight.Recommended.

author: Melissa Headland
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 17, 2022
content: First impression is that the product overall is good value for money. Only issue noted is that the USB-C connection lacks the bandwidth to support a true 6 in 1. For example, with a USB keyboard, USB mic, USB mouse, USB-C charger, and HDMI second monitor plugged in, the mouse is very jittery when moving across the screen. If you unplug the HDMI, for instance, the freed up bandwidth now permits the mouse to scroll smoothly. If you are buying and intend to use all 6 ports, use caution that the single USB-C connection may not be able to properly support them all.

date: Reviewed in the United States on April 5, 2021
content: This product (or one like it) is almost necessary for a modern laptop. My new HP Envy x360 only came with 2 USB ports and no ethernet port. This product has performed it's function as adequately as I could hope. Ethernet works well from it's ethernet port, and it even allows an extra HDMI input. Occasionally I use an audio interface that doesn't like to be plugged into the hub (I think it might have to do with needing some sort of priority - or it just doesn't like the technology). It has to be plugged into one of the 2 USB ports on my computer in order to create buffers. So don't expect all products to work perfectly plugged into the hub. That being said, it definitely solves essentially every issue I have in one nice box.

author: J T
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 29, 2019
content: I am using Samsung Tab A (2019) 10.1"  tables as pay clock kiosks for employees to punch in/out. The tables only have 1-USB type C port. These devices enable me to hardwire ethernet to the tablets and charge them at the same time. 1 star short because the cables are just too short. I am using 2 of the Vida mount enclosures https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B07VB9QFXQ/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_title_o08_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1and this device sits nicely behind the enclosure inside the mount, but I needed to get a couple of extension cables because the cables do not reach the USB input on the tablet when using an enclosure. These devices would work great for people using tablets in a point of sale environment but you will need extensions. The device itself is about 3.9" long. The cable length measured from where it exits the device to the tip of the USB connector is 5.75". The cable length only with out the connector is 4.75". If the cable was about 4" longer it would have served my purpose without having to add extensions.

author: GBarrington
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 8, 2024
content: I'm experimenting with replacing my Windows PC with a higher end tablet.  so I wanted a docking station  (let's call it the DS) to connect it to a mouse, keyboard, and most i importantly, my 28 inch display screen.  So Far, So Good!  This review is going through the docking station, the S9, and DEX, then displayed on a nice big screen!  I REALLY like using a REAL keyboard!Once it was delivered, I rushed to my workstation to see how it worked.  And it didn't!  Nothing, NOTHING would work.  It kept telling me to check the cables.  So out of frustration, I had lunch.It turned out that the case I bought for the S9 fooled me into thinking I had the DS plugged into the tablet, but it was not.  Once I had figured THAT out, the docking station, and the tablet worked well together.I like that I'm using two different RF Dongles for the keyboard and mouse plugged into the DS.  I don't have to use battery power to use Bluetooth for those accessories.  Plus, I still have one USB 3.0 port free.  The Keyboard and Mouse don't appear to lag, at all.  If it does, it is so minor that I am unable to percieve it.I like that I can power the Tablet from the DS.  I'm using a 20 watt Amazon charger, and it seems to work just fine.  The tablet doesn't give me any messages that I'm on a slow charge and it seems to charge as it does without the DS.The only real negative is that the cable from the DS to the Tab S9 is a bit too short for the tablet to be propped upright.  The tablet display remains on, and the S Pen can be used with it.  I'm thinking that I might want to use the tablet itself as a sort of touchpad sometimes.  I might find applications where I would want the tablet display to remain upright.  I don't know, but it MIGHT be a problem, maybe.Build quality seems good.  I think the DS case is metal, at least it looks and feels like aluminum.  And the cord going to the Tablet seems quite robust.  I can't comment yet on reliabiy,  It will take some time for that info to appear.  But functionally, it is everything the seller claims it is.  I am satisfied.
