author: Randall R. Brachmann
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 10, 2024
content: I needed a powered port expander for my DELL laptop.  I was having issues with data/communication to my printer and I read that a powered port extender would solve this.  This is the right tool for the job with a few caveats.  The multi-port is solid and well built and lightweight for travel.  My new DELL Inspiron 16 uses a smart power adapter.  The system must have a minimum of 65 watts to boot up.  When I attach the power adapter to the muli-port and then the multi-port to the laptop, get a message about a weak charge (see attached photo).  Working with the vendor and their support team, we tried several options.  They even sent me a 2nd unit at no added charge.  Sadly, the problem was still showing.  I suspect the smart power adaptor is sensing the draw of the multi-port regardless of the laptop and stepping down to a lower wattage.  Ultimately, I connected the power adapter directly to the laptop and then used a spare power adapter just for the multi-port.  My laptop now reboots properly and I have the powered multi-port I needed to support an additional display (HDMI), HP Desk Jet (USB 3.0), I-Book (standalone hard drive), a spare USB 3.0 port for thumb drive, and a port for my original non-powered 4-port USB extender which I still use for my free-standing keyboard, and my laptop vent (fan) system.  The USB-C cable used to connect the multi-port to the laptop is about 5 inches long, so I had some rearranging to make this spaghetti mess to workout.  I'm told it's to minimize data loss/corruption to drives, monitors, etc.  Everything now works great.The support team was very helpful and patient.  Never condescending or argumentative.  They responded to my original review the next day and offered a refund or a new device while we worked on the problem.  I kept the device and didn't seek a refund.  I'm very happy with them.  Do I wish it worked with the laptop adapter instead of a 2nd adapter?  Sure, but I don't see this as their problem but something with the DELL.

content: I am so glad that I can come back and revise my below review. After I was dissatisfied with the product I received, I wrote below review. UTech customer support contacted me. author: Tech Tango
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2018
content: This adapter packs a lot of features into a small 12cm device, and is perfectly usable as a portable "mini-Dock".Linux?  Windows 10?  Android?  Yes!The design is a sleek metal case, seamless, with no visible screws.Slender, with no parts to lose, takes up very little space in the bag -- about as much as two Sharpie pens.It has a captive 6-inch cable with USB-C, and connections for USB-C PD, HDMI, Ethernet, and three USB 3.0 (blue) sockets.  Inside is a USB Hub, Ethernet Adapter, and HDMI display (&audio) output.The HDMI output is driven by your computer's internal graphics adapter, so the second monitor is integrated into both Windows and Linux with no additional drivers.  I believe it's done with a Via Labs VL100 "Billboard" Display Alternate mode adapter for USB-C, so it adds a second Monitor/Display instance, but not a new Display Adapter.The USB xHCI hub (VIA Labs 2109:0817 VL812 Super Speed Hub) appears on the bus, and this provides the three open USB ports as well as the new Ethernet Controller.  It's a Realtek USB GbE Family Controller:  VID: 0bda and PID: 8153.  Drivers were automatically available in both Ubuntu Linux and Windows 10.  It linked up to a 1Gb Ethernet as normal, no prompts or settings needed.For the adventurous, this UtechSmart device also works with the Samsung Galaxy S9+, and surprisingly well!Plug a USB Thumbdrive into the ports and it appears as a Storage Device, perfect for copying pictures off the phone.The Ethernet works as well, and automatically gets a DHCP address and switches over to wired connection.The HDMI monitor shows a clone of the Galaxy S9+ screen in perfect detail.  Best to rotate the phone to horizontal to make the most of the monitor.  (Sorry, no Samsung Dex environment here, but a USB Mouse and Keyboard work just fine.)Powering the adapter also charges the phone, as expected, but not as fast as a direct connection.  I was more impressed that the phone happily powered the whole adapter, with HDMI, Ethernet, and USB from its own battery, no problem.I was going to poke fun at the whole Phone + Adapter + Monitor, Ethernet, USB Drive, Keyboard, Mouse, but now that it's been running for a while on my desk, I'm imagining it could be useful if you intend to be at your phone for hours, hammering out email or Amazon reviews.All in all, this is a really nice piece of kit to have in your travel bag, or as a single-connection desktop dock.  It has replaced my USB-On-The-Go (OTG) adapters, as those were always a bit sketchy with some USB devices, and prevented charging..  Even if I don't need all the features, it's small enough on the bag that it's replaced a number of other adapters already.I accepted an offer to test and review this device, and received it for free, but this is my honest and unbiased review.  Pictures are my own.

author: AMC
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 22, 2019
content: I gave this 5 stars because even though it isn't perfect, I think any issues I've encountered are more likely a result of the hardware, software, and drivers I'm using.  TL;DR: It basically works as expected and I can confirm that it doesn't use DisplayLink.  I contacted UTechSmart before purchase to confirm if this device used USB-C HDMI Alt-mode instead of a DisplayLink chip.  They confirmed it uses the former and said that though they had not tested it with a Pocket 2, if it didn't work I could return it no questions asked.  Bonus points to them for that.  For reference, I'm using it with a GPD Pocket 2 (late 2018 product refresh using an Intel m3-8100Y CPU), running Windows 10 LTSC 2019 and a mixture of GPD and first-party drivers (mostly direct from Intel and Realtek).  This is not how it comes from GPD, and is most definitely NOT a supported configuration by either GPD or Microsoft.  I'm using the latest Intel drivers available (26.20.100.7000) from the Intel site.  The only persistent issue is that on my device, if second-screen mode default (Win+P) is set to duplicate or extend then neither screen will display when the hub is first plugged in.  After a few seconds one of the screens will start working again.  If the default is second screen only then it will work immediately.  Once external display is working, using the Win+P shortcut to switch to duplicate or extend works correctly.  This is most likely a Windows or driver issue.  For reference the Pocket 2 has a 1920x1200 screen that I use at 150% scaling and I mostly used 1920x1080 @100% scale monitors for testing.  No HDMI adapters were used and I tested with two different known-good cables.  Monitors tested were two Dell S2240L, one LG IPS234, and a Panasonic TCP50GT25.  I also tested on a 4k Samsung UN50NU6950 and it reported output 4k@30fps, which is close enough to the Intel UHD 615 spec for HDMI 1.4.  This hub can function without external power, but if you have problems, try connecting power before you connect it to your computer.  When I used it for the first time, it wouldn't appear to work without external power, but after some unrelated software and driver updates, now it does.  For me, this issue was definitely on the host side, not the hub side.  The network chip is a Realtek RTL8153 USB 3 to gigabit Ethernet adapter.  I own several devices that use this chip and it is serviceable, but tends to reset or drop out under sustained gigabit traffic.  This is a characteristic of either the chip or Realtek's drivers, and there isn't really anything UTechSmart can do about it.  (The other common providers of low cost USB->Ethernet chips (e.g. the ASIX AX88179) often have the same problems.)  Below max speed, the 8153 works without any problems.  As an aside, if you have one of these chips in a standalone usb adapter, you can plug it into a USB 2 port to get a trouble-free 250-350 Mb/s without having to babysit it.I haven't tried stress-testing how much power you can get from the USB 3.0 ports, nor have I tried to saturate the USB-C link with simultaneous video, network, and USB SSD file transfer traffic.  It doesn't really fit my use case for the device, and if doing so didn't work or caused the hub to drop connection it wouldn't necessarily be the hub's fault anyway.  One feature of the GPD Pocket 2 is that it can charge from any 5V source, not just from a USB-C PD charger.  So I tried to power the hub with a regular USB power bank that can output 5V@1.8A (Soshine E3S).  When charging directly, the Pocket 2 increases current draw until the voltage begins to sag below 5V.  This is normal behavior and prevents the device from pulling too much current from the charger.  But when I power the hub and indirectly charge the device, the power bank's over-current protection immediately trips.  For whatever reason, the hub prevents the Pocket 2 from noticing the voltage drop in time to prevent a fault.  A higher output 5V source, or a proper USB-C PD power bank would probably work just fine.  It's just too much for a smaller power bank.So in summary it works well, the price ($40 at time of purchase) is competitive with other similar products, and if I needed another I would start looking at UTechSmart first.

author: Jo Sutton
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 20, 2023
content: The UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter has all all the ports I needed. When I tried to charge my iPhone with a cable that had a type C plug on one end and a Lightning on the other, it wouldn't charge . I tried with many other adaptor cable and it didn't work, so I thought it was faulty.  I contacted the company and they communicated to me that the Type C port worked for charging computers but it was a one way port that didn't work on other devices. They actually said that they were going to communicate this issue to the manufacturers and see if they could upgrade that issue to make it a two way port. They issued me a full refund, even though I decided to keep it because in essence, it was fully functional. So, I say, it works great... and customer service really wants us to be happy and to improve their products. I think if we continue to treat companies like people and not expect perfection, but to stay in communication, then we can enjoy good relationships, however big, or seemingly impersonal. They are not impersonal at all. Eventually, I asked my representative for her name, since we had gone back and forth in communication so often. I am pleased. I trust this company.

date: Reviewed in the United States on July 23, 2023
content: The UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter is a great small and versatile tool. I use it to connect my Android phone or tablet to an HDMI display that is not a smart device. I primarily use it in my kids' room to watch Netflix or YouTube videos on the larger screen, or in our travel van where I have a display for the kids to watch TV while on long travels.I love this tool because it eliminates the need for DVDs, which can get scratched and the kids get tired of watching the same movies. With this tool, I can connect their device to the display, and they can watch everything together on the display and listen through my van speakers.The tool also has other great benefits that I use with my Mac, such as the ability to connect USB devices for external storage, connect to an HDMI display, or connect to Ethernet cables. This is a great tool to have in your computer bag, especially if you use a Mac or any other computer with a USB C port.Pros:Small and lightweightVersatileEasy to useAffordableWorks with a variety of devicesCons:The HDMI port only supports 4K output at 30fpsThe Ethernet port does not support Gigabit speedsOverall:I highly recommend the UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter. It is a great tool for anyone who needs to connect their devices to a variety of displays or peripherals.Overall, I am very happy with the UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter. It is a great product that I would recommend to anyone.

author: Ross
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 21, 2018
content: Ever since I got the new style of MacBook Pro I've been looking for the perfect dongle. It's a running joke that Mac users carry a bag full of dongles, and unfortunately there's some truth to it - in my backpack I have a pouch with 2x USB-A to C adapters and a USB-C to HDMI adapter. If you're looking for a solid way to simplify things you've found it.Admittedly I'd never bought a USB-C to ethernet adapter, but I had one for my older MacBook because it's good to have from time to time. This one works quite well in that regard - I'm getting gigabit speeds. I attached a speed test showing over 900 up, but my Mac shows a 1000 tx rate in network settings.The USB ports work as expected for USB 3.0. I put an image of the system report, but's showing a 5 GB speed and the transfer speeds seem to reflect that. 3 ports is a pretty generous amount - I'd almost consider a smaller adapter with 2, but if your complaint is too many USB ports that's a good sign. Unfortunately the world is not ready to live without USB type A, and this adapter has a lot of it.The HDMI adapter is 4k 30hz, and that's the best you're going to get on a multipart dongle. I've done my research looking for this exact adapter with 4k 60hz and while I've found a few that claim it, it's always 4k 30hz. If you want 60hz you need to get a stand-alone USB-C to HDMI adapter with no other ports (like the one I mentioned above). I put a photo of my Mac recognizing my 4k TV's resolution (3480x2160).The power delivery works - it charged my 15" Macbook successfully. It has 60w power delivery, so depending on your computer that may be slower than what you're used to. The 15 inch MacBook charger is 85w, but it also has 4 ports available so the power delivery isn't particularly necessary. For the 13 inch Macs with 2 ports the charger is 60w, so this will work fine. If you have the 12 inch MacBook with 1 port this would be a lifesaver - everything you need to make it usable.Overall it's a great adapter and does as well as it potentially can for every port it offers. It has an indicator light when it's on that I'm not sure actually serves any function, but the build quality is great. Aesthetically it looks great (and would look great with a space grey MacBook), though I will admit that I wish it was offered in silver to match mine. It's replaced 3 adapters I used to carry and I've gained power delivery, 1 USB port, and gigabit ethernet. The only question is durability, and if it continues to perform this way this thing checks every box. I will be sure to update my review if I have any problems with it (and how they are resolved).

author: Jo Sutton
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 20, 2023
content: The UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter has all all the ports I needed. When I tried to charge my iPhone with a cable that had a type C plug on one end and a Lightning on the other, it wouldn't charge . I tried with many other adaptor cable and it didn't work, so I thought it was faulty.  I contacted the company and they communicated to me that the Type C port worked for charging computers but it was a one way port that didn't work on other devices. They actually said that they were going to communicate this issue to the manufacturers and see if they could upgrade that issue to make it a two way port. They issued me a full refund, even though I decided to keep it because in essence, it was fully functional. So, I say, it works great... and customer service really wants us to be happy and to improve their products. I think if we continue to treat companies like people and not expect perfection, but to stay in communication, then we can enjoy good relationships, however big, or seemingly impersonal. They are not impersonal at all. Eventually, I asked my representative for her name, since we had gone back and forth in communication so often. I am pleased. I trust this company.

author: Eye View
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 23, 2023
content: The UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter is a great small and versatile tool. I use it to connect my Android phone or tablet to an HDMI display that is not a smart device. I primarily use it in my kids' room to watch Netflix or YouTube videos on the larger screen, or in our travel van where I have a display for the kids to watch TV while on long travels.I love this tool because it eliminates the need for DVDs, which can get scratched and the kids get tired of watching the same movies. With this tool, I can connect their device to the display, and they can watch everything together on the display and listen through my van speakers.The tool also has other great benefits that I use with my Mac, such as the ability to connect USB devices for external storage, connect to an HDMI display, or connect to Ethernet cables. This is a great tool to have in your computer bag, especially if you use a Mac or any other computer with a USB C port.Pros:Small and lightweightVersatileEasy to useAffordableWorks with a variety of devicesCons:The HDMI port only supports 4K output at 30fpsThe Ethernet port does not support Gigabit speedsOverall:I highly recommend the UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter. It is a great tool for anyone who needs to connect their devices to a variety of displays or peripherals.Overall, I am very happy with the UtechSmart USB C Ethernet Multiport Adapter. It is a great product that I would recommend to anyone.

author: Ross
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 21, 2018
content: Ever since I got the new style of MacBook Pro I've been looking for the perfect dongle. It's a running joke that Mac users carry a bag full of dongles, and unfortunately there's some truth to it - in my backpack I have a pouch with 2x USB-A to C adapters and a USB-C to HDMI adapter. If you're looking for a solid way to simplify things you've found it.Admittedly I'd never bought a USB-C to ethernet adapter, but I had one for my older MacBook because it's good to have from time to time. This one works quite well in that regard - I'm getting gigabit speeds. I attached a speed test showing over 900 up, but my Mac shows a 1000 tx rate in network settings.The USB ports work as expected for USB 3.0. I put an image of the system report, but's showing a 5 GB speed and the transfer speeds seem to reflect that. 3 ports is a pretty generous amount - I'd almost consider a smaller adapter with 2, but if your complaint is too many USB ports that's a good sign. Unfortunately the world is not ready to live without USB type A, and this adapter has a lot of it.The HDMI adapter is 4k 30hz, and that's the best you're going to get on a multipart dongle. I've done my research looking for this exact adapter with 4k 60hz and while I've found a few that claim it, it's always 4k 30hz. If you want 60hz you need to get a stand-alone USB-C to HDMI adapter with no other ports (like the one I mentioned above). I put a photo of my Mac recognizing my 4k TV's resolution (3480x2160).The power delivery works - it charged my 15" Macbook successfully. It has 60w power delivery, so depending on your computer that may be slower than what you're used to. The 15 inch MacBook charger is 85w, but it also has 4 ports available so the power delivery isn't particularly necessary. For the 13 inch Macs with 2 ports the charger is 60w, so this will work fine. If you have the 12 inch MacBook with 1 port this would be a lifesaver - everything you need to make it usable.Overall it's a great adapter and does as well as it potentially can for every port it offers. It has an indicator light when it's on that I'm not sure actually serves any function, but the build quality is great. Aesthetically it looks great (and would look great with a space grey MacBook), though I will admit that I wish it was offered in silver to match mine. It's replaced 3 adapters I used to carry and I've gained power delivery, 1 USB port, and gigabit ethernet. The only question is durability, and if it continues to perform this way this thing checks every box. I will be sure to update my review if I have any problems with it (and how they are resolved).

author: PhoenixM
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 19, 2022
content: I'm honestly surprised that this hub has 60% 5-star reviews.I (IT guy) bought this to go along with a brand new Dell Latitude 5520 (Win 10x64) for my boss, so as to give him additional ports and fewer things to plug/unplug every day. It has not performed as expected.1. It has two HDMI ports, but if you plug a monitor into both of them, the computer locks up (not a BSoD; simply frozen and unresponsive). The only way to unfreeze it when this happens is to unplug the hub itself, i.e. even unplugging the second monitor from the hub does not unfreeze it. Note that having one monitor plugged into the hub and one monitor plugged into the laptop's onboard HDMI port is fine; it's just two on the hub simultaneously that doesn't seem to work.2. The RJ-45 Ethernet port loses connection for a minute or two multiple times per day. This problem doesn't happen when using the laptop's on-board RJ-45 port. And there's nothing in the network's DHCP logs suggesting lease renegotiation issues or anything like that; the port on the hub is simply losing connectivity for unknown reasons.Price was one of the determining factors when I made the purchase, and clearly we got what we paid for.Edit (2024-Jan-02): A coworker bought one of these also, in late 2022, and also had trouble with the network connection dropping. He told me at that time that he had contacted the manufacturer, and they sent him a replacement free of charge. I happened to stop by his office last month, and noticed that he was VPNed into the network via wi-fi, and not connected to Ethernet; when I asked him about it, he said that the Ethernet port on the replacement hub was also unable to maintain a reliable, consistent connection.So that's three separate hubs with a bad Ethernet port, folks. Make of that what you will.

content: So I  get this and I realize I had to buy a USB-c adapter because my laptop doesn't have the C port. Then I  got the adapter, plugged it into the USB port y nada. author: Andy Kim
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 24, 2021
content: This is a very low quality adapter, and the one I got didn't even work right. I'm lucky it didn't damage my MacBook. I thought I could save some money by getting this cheaper hub, however that was a bad idea. This is the cheapest one on Amazon for a reason. The one I got didn't recognize any USB 3.0 drives in the 3.0 ports, it would only see USB 2.0 devices. The worst part of this adapter is that the USB ports are actually backwards! This does not matter for most devices, however you can see the how it is an issue with devices like my Samsung flash drive in the picture. I would not be able to plug that flash drive in if the machine was flat against the desk. All of those issues combined with how cheap and light this adapter is make me recommend staying far away from it. I can't even imagine how cheap the charging circuitry must be inside, I would not feel safe charging my MacBook through this.

author: Gabe
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 28, 2022
content: I bought this last December, and while it was initially working well, its consistently gotten worse over time.  The main culprit is how light the actual docking station is.  The HDMI cords for my dual monitors are thick and lift the light docking station up off my desk.  This causes an issue with being able to read the HDMI port inputs for some reason (weird angles?) and then causes my laptop to think the Type-C input is not there, causing my keyboard and mouse to stop working as the computer cannot connect with them.  I have a standing desk, so I have tried adjusted the angles of the wires to get it to sit properly, but if i make one slight move, the connects fails and I end up spending 10-30minutes playing with the wires before I MIGHT get them to all work again.Simply put, not worth the money or the headache.

author: Ian Andersen
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 22, 2019
content: the instruction manual says you can do an extended display on two monitors if one is using VGA and the other is using HDMI; this is false.  I tried multiple ways using virtually every port on the thing; hdmi, vga, usb, usbc... and multiple combinations of all of them, nothing worked.  It will only mirror the two external displays on a macbook.  i went to the support site .... good luck there, half the pages are broken, manual doesn't load, support form is broken.  all copy in instructions in manual and on site reads like someone misspelled a bunch of words in another language and then ran it through google translate and hoped for the best.  it also got ridiculously hot in less than a minute after plugging in.  i've been bitten before by cheaper chinese made stuff, and i should know better, but let my error serve some purpose - PASS ON THIS PRODUCT!

author: Sujit Patel
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 15, 2020
content: I connected my two monitors to this hub so that I could use my two larger external monitors while working from home instead of just the laptop screen. Unfortunately, the two monitors that were connected to the hub would simultaneously lose their connection to the hub. At first, they would lose their connection and then a couple of seconds later they would be fine. Eventually, they would completely lose their connection to the hub and all of a sudden i would have two blank monitors. I would have to unplug and plug everything several times before the connection to the hub was restored. This became extremely frustrating as it began to happen several times a day in the middle of working or while on a work call. I eventually gave up on this product and purchased a slightly more expensive Dell Universal Dock which has had no issues so far.

author: Lexxi
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 21, 2020
content: I bought this in January and was using it for 2 external monitors + laptop + keyboard/mouse. It worked great at handling the 3 displays. At the time I was WFH one day per week and mostly had no issues. It does get a bit warm but I propped it up on some mechanical pencils and it was fine.Starting in March when I became WFH 5 days per week, I started having issues. In the morning, the dock wouldn't connect with the monitors and I would have to unplug and replug everything multiple times to get all 3 displays working. The same would happen if I turned off the computer for lunch. I would spend anywhere from 15-45 minutes trying to get the dock to properly show all 3 screens. This became a daily fight. I ended up buying a more expensive Thinkpad dock and haven't had any issues.

date: Reviewed in the United States on November 30, 2020
content: I had another adapter before, but It had a couple of problems:- It was always hot af- The pass-through charging power was limited so that my MacBook was actually draining the battery while on power- It was attached via a short cable and not directly inserted into two USB-c ports on the sideThis one doesn't have any of the problems mentioned above + some YouTube reviews say I'll get faster speeds over USB, though I'm yet to test thatOverall, I hate what apple did to the ports on MacBooks, but this dongle seems to be the most viable solution so far.UPDATE:1 day after I wrote a positive review, the thing just broke and I had to go back to my old adapter :|

The extremely fast 1000M Ethernet port helps gamers and office workers download movies or music faster, transfer files faster, and reduce latency in use.
【Broad Compatibility】Our USB C docking station is widely used for laptops with Windows 10/11, Mac OS, Chrome OS, Dell XPS 13/15, Dell Latitude/Precision, Lenovo ThinkPad X1 Carbon, HP Spectre x360/ZBook or other devices with USB Type-C (Gen 2)/Thunderbolt 3/4 ports which supports "Displayport Alt Mode". Recycled materials

author: Joseph N.
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 13, 2022
content: I love how practical this is (when it works). The ability to connect everything to this is much better than having to connect and disconnect half a dozen cords to the laptop everything you mo e somewhere.With all of that said, mine randomly will stop powering the mechanical keyboard and the external monitor will start turning on and off rapidly. The only solution to the above is to disconnect the station and reconnect it.My brother does have the exact same model (and we both use the same exact laptop model) and has zero issues. Unfortunately I am outside the return window and stuck with mine just 45 days after purchasing.

author: Soccer Coach
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 20, 2020
content: I purchased the UCN3270 to function as a docking station for my HP Elitebook 840 G4 laptop.  The User Guide.pdf document on the Amazon website claimed the docking station was compatible with the HP Elitebook 840.  However, the HP Elitebook 840 model does not have a USB-C port that supports Displayport video until model G5 or higher.  This is a very subtle nuance that is lost in the product marketing.  The HP Elitebook 840 G4 model does have a USB-C port, but that port is only enabled for data only, not data and video.  The UCN3270 product works very well when paired with a laptop that has a USB-C port that supports Displayport video (such as a Lenovo X280).  Disappointing false advertising in the User Guide.pdf file posted on Amazon's product page.

author: Professor
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 26, 2022
content: The hub worked fine for the first week I had it. After about ten days one of the HDMI ports on the hub stopped working. (I tested by switching which monitor I plugged into a given HDMI port on the hub, and one port consistently didn't work, the other one did). Now the USB-A port is going out intermittently as well.I used it with my Lenovo Yoga 7i, which has thunderbolt 4 ports. I connected: two 1080p displays via HDMI, ethernet, power supply (the Lenovo 65w USB-C charger that came with my laptop), and a USB-A hub.Returning. Thankful for Amazon's return policy.

author: Claire G.
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2020
content: I ordered this hub after seeing youtube reviews. Picture clearly shows "UtechSmart" on amazon and I received a hub with completely different branding -- I cannot even pronounce the brand. Same ports, but they are also in a different order, so it's clearly not the same device.More importantly, the connections are horribly loose so the hub is constantly sliding out and disconnecting all my devices if my laptop is just barely moved on the desk. So, because I hookup my webcam to this hub, my video randomly disconnects in video conferencing calls sometimes.I guess you get what you pay for. Find a company with a reputable brand instead!

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 10, 2019
content: I purchased this product to use with my laptop and two external monitors.  The monitors cannot be detected when the HDMI is plugged into this system (my wireless keyboard does work when USB is plugged into docking station, however).  I called customer service.  The call line sends you through to an automatic voicemail box.  I left a message and received NO response!  I gave them the benefit of the doubt and returned the first docking station I received and purchased a new one.  I just tried the second docking station and it also does not work when the HDMI's are plugged in.  I won't even bother calling customer service this time.  I will be returning this product and not repurchasing.

author: It's just me
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 3, 2020
content: I have a HP Laptop (15.6" Gaming Laptop - AMD Ryzen 5 - 8GB Memory - NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1050 - 256GB Solid State Drive - Shadow Black, Chrome Green, Paint Finish) and 2 HP monitors. This docking station would not talk to each other. I contacted Tech Support, like I was instructed; I waited 4 days and still no response. To this day (over a month later) I still have not heard from them; needless to say after 4 days of no response I returned the product and bought a docking station from a different company. I am not saying this is a bad docking station, I am just saying it did not work with my laptop and monitors.

author: T. Weidner
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 1, 2020
content: I got this docking station and the HDMI ports stopped working in less than 24 hours.  There are 2 HDMI ports and after the 1st day, my laptop would only recognize 2 Monitors. It duplicated the monitors.  It would not "detect" the monitors hooked up  to this port as separate monitors (yet the first day of hookup, it did).  It treated them as one.  I did the extend the displays, but it only extended to the laptop monitor and still treated my 2 external monitors as one.  Useless!  I don't understand why it worked fine the 1st day and then not.

author: Amazon Customer
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 19, 2020
content: Bought product think it would be a cheaper docking station then a Dell. Big mistake. Hooked it all up even bought a Thunderbolt 3 adaptor hooked up to USB 3.0 in computer. Keyboard/mouse fine; two external hard drives both available on my computer; the two monitors total failure, wouldn’t even hook up to one monitor. Tried to contact support they told be to contact Amazon support. Spent 2 hours with them found out the dock station is only good for one monitor. In my case no monitors. Decided to return and spend the extra $100 for a Dell station that I know will work.

author: Ashley C
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 3, 2021
content: We bought two of these for our office to run dual 2560x1440 displays off our laptops. The descriptions says, "...supports single and dual HDMI displays up to 3840x2160@30Hz" however, when we connected to our monitors (with HDMI cables to both) one dropped in resolution. Also while trying to troubleshoot this we also noticed one of the USB's was dropping out intermittently. The one we were using went back in the box and both have been returned. It's a nice looking product but certainly doesn't do what it says it will.

author: Nancy
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 9, 2021
content: Update 4-15: I have been using this dock without issue for 3 months and only wrote my original review a few days ago after 3-months of use. Two days ago, my computer started making the USB connect/disconnect sound over and over. Investigating the issue, the card reader ports on this doc are continually being disconnected and then reconnected by Windows. Everything is pointing to a driver issue. Unfortunately, the manufacturer does not have a driver for this dock. I have reached out to the company's support email address, but as of yet have received no response. I can no longer recommend this docking station and have reduced my rating to 2 stars. I am still able to use the dock for keyboard, mouse, and an external monitor, but the annoyance of the constant USB notifications is going to push me to a different dock. I will update again if/when I hear back from the company.Summary: This is a great little dock but you will need to provide the power supply...I would recommend this as a budget friendly docking station to support an external monitor and peripherals.This little dock is great, completely plug and play. I took it out of the box, plugged the peripherals (mouse and keyboard), monitor (HDMI), and the power supply from my kids Switch, connected it to my HP laptop and everything worked great!The only issue I have run into is that sometimes the computer doesn't charge through the dock. This is likely due to the Switch's power supply being underpowered for charging the laptop and running the peripherals at the same time.

author: Curtis Kilgore
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 6, 2020
content: First of all, if you have a macbook pro this will not work for two screens. I am speaking for my macbook pro 2019 I am not sure if theres a different result on older models. If you hook up two or more monitors to this thing the monitors will have the same exact screen. They can't work as their own. I had one hooked up to the hdmi and the other two the vga. Second, this docking station gets very hot. I have had to hook up two of them because I had another one I was going to sell once I got this one, but since this one doesn't work for dual external monitors I had to keep it in order to use both monitors separately. Finally and most important, it blew out the usb-c port it was connected to. I then googled what to do and was told by many forums to try and do a simple "sms reset" which could possibly fix the port, but instead it blew out my batter and destroyed my logic board aka "mother board" and I lost my data and had to take it in to be repaired. I have to believe that my port going out and then this happening to my batter/logic board were connected because an smc reset is harmless. My macbook pro 2019 was only 3 months old.  I am only giving this two stars because you if you can remember to unplug and or not let it run all day every day it might not end up happening with the same result. But it gets very hot very quickly so if you can find another docking station that fits your needs I highly recommend getting that one.

author: Maddi Diaz
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 15, 2023
content: I’m a photographer and work on my MacBook Air daily. I got this because my old dock broke. I usually have my second monitor, hard drive, keyboard (usb), and an sd card plugged in at once. But you move even a little (I mean even sneeze) it ejects everything.

author: John Ratliff
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 23, 2022
content: They claim it will do 2 monitors at 4K resolution. I have one 1920x1080 screen and one 2560x1080 screen. If I plug both monitors into the dock, I am restricted to 1920x1080 on both. I have to plug one of the monitors into the HDMI port on my laptop and the other into the HDMI port on the dock. I wanted a single cable. I have a much more expensive Lenovo dock that will do both monitors at the correct resolution, but I didn't want to cart it back and forth between the office and home. The only reason I'm not returning it is it has more ports than the the StarTech dock I'm replacing. I've gone from 4 cables I have to plug in at home to 2, but I really wanted just one.

author: Desert Bum
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 30, 2022
content: With a M1 Monterey MacBk, I had trouble with a USB2 dock attached -  On that attached dock, some items worked, others did not (Printers, scanners, USB bluetooth dongle for mouse). Also when I used a USB-C extension cable, again items didn’t work. Sounds like something on my end, however when replacing this dock with another similar USB-C dock (Totu)- everything worked.It may be a compatibility thing of Thunderbolt vs USB-C, but again the other (older) dock works fine.My Advice- before your Amazon 30 days expire:1- Attach a USB2 dock to this dock. On that attached dock, see if your printer still works and your iPhone registers.2- Try 1 again but with an extension cable (if you’ll need one) between the Mac and this dock.if everything still works for you-  ignore this review.

author: silentbob343
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2019
content: I don't typically write rviews, but I thought this could provide useful to those looking at this item with a Dell XPS13 7390 2-in-1.Two observations:1.  When plugging in the XPS13 powersupply, factory, and then plugging the hub in to the laptop I was greeted with a message at startup letting me know that the charging device detected would not be able to power the laptop entirely on its own and would require battery usage.2.  High pitched noise coming from the the hub when the Dell XPS13 powersupply was plugged in.  This noise sounds like a coil whine, but is most likely some type of ground loop issue.Both of these issues could be a product of the Dell's power supply, but in either case it does not seem to be a good match for the XPS13 7390 2-in-1.  While writing this review I realized I only tried this product with one outlet and perhaps should try additonal outlets in my home to make sure that wasn't part of the issue.  I will try it in additional outlets and update the review with those results.  If I experience the same behavior it will be going back.

date: Reviewed in the United States on May 25, 2023
content: First issue I had was that it didn't like me using HDMI for both of my monitors. author: AJH
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 30, 2020
content: I bought this to support two 4k LG 27" monitors, from my Thinkpad X1 (Gen. 6) laptop, it does not.  I was able to get two dual 1080 displays working without out issue, and I got my laptop screen to work as the 3rd display.  When I upgraded to dual 4k monitors, it looks like I ran out of bandwidth as one monitor will display full 4k resolution and the second 4k monitor is locked in at 800x600.  If I plug one monitor into my laptop I THEN get both monitors to display as 4k. Another negative is that the chord is too short, and the unit will get really hot.That said, It did a great job with the two 1080 monitors, it charged my laptop and it read UHS-2 SD cards without issue.  It also worked well with my ipad pro as a usb hub so I may keep it just for that, but it doesn't support dual 4k and that's what I bought it.

date: Reviewed in the United States on September 8, 2020
content: I bought the hub, mainly to connect the monitor to my laptop(Dell XPS 13 7390), but also to connect other external devices such as a wireless keyboard and mouse, an external SSD, etc. (Recent laptops come with very few ports to accommodate all these needs) But now, I  frequently experience two problems:1. a notification for insufficient power delivery on my laptop, when the power source is connected through the hub.2. no signal on my monitor( as if the power was insufficient), after being connected for a while.NOTE: My laptop is listed on the compatible devices.I had no issues with the delivery process and with the quality of the material on the device.

content: Used the hub with two HP monitors and a Dell laptop for work. First, the monitors disconnect and then reconnect multiple times during the day. author: S Tyler Constantine
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 26, 2020
content: I've used a different USB-C adapter for HDMI single monitor for a long time. Got this because I was upgrading to a dual monitor setup and wanted 2 HDMI outputs.It works fine, I can extend my display across both screens no issues.However, a major gripe - the thing does not wake up the monitors from sleep. My other USB-C hub does not have this problem. I'll be returning this one for a refund.

content: I purchased this unit 10/2022.  Was only able to use the Dual HDMI and 1 USB for the printer.  Did not try to use Ethernet. author: Zev Feller
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 10, 2023
content: I bought this because Apple is very stingy with the ports on its sub-$1500 laptops. It works, and doesn't heat up that much, even when the usb-c, the HDMI, and two of the usb-a ports are in use. However, I have two problems with it. First of all, despite its metallic construction, it doesn't feel very sturdy, like it could snap in half if i put down my laptop at a bad angle. Secondly, and more importantly, there's only one usb-c port, and that's often taken by the charger. I'd rather have another usb-c port available, even if at the cost of one of the three usb-a ports. Beyond those issues, I have no other complaints. It works well for what it's supposed to, and doesn't cost that much either.–UPDATE–The seller contacted me and apologized for the inconvenience, and refunded the purchase. I appreciate their willingness to help, and this is one of the best customer services I've interacted with. I'll probably buy one of their other USB-C hubs.

author: Mr. Nelson
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 6, 2023
content: I have purchased about 20 of these over the last 2 years.  All of which worked flawlessly out the box.  Now I have about 5 of them sitting at my desk that I can no longer use.  The 2nd HDMI port starts to behave unreliably.  Sometimes you can mess with it and get it to come back online.  But its a big hassle.  I have read through these reviews and its apparent this issue happens to many others.  It's also apparent that the company will refund the price of the unit, if you're willing to raise your review to 4 stars or above.  Very shady if you ask me.  But read the reviews and you will see for yourself.  Are you buying a good solid product or are you buying customer support?  Expect that your HDMI port will begin to act up.  Dont believe me, keep reading the reviews.

author: Michael Ross
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 7, 2020
content: I bought this to use with my work-issued Dell Latitude 7400 (instead of paying hundreds for the port replicator that Dell makes specifically for their laptops) and a dual monitor setup. It works great, except for when it doesn't, but that's only in a few instances:- By default, when I plug the replicator into my laptop, I get the Windows 10 desktop across both screens (which is what I want), however if have it plugged in prior to starting up the laptop or the laptop is awaking from sleep, it goes to screen mirroring mode, where both screens are the same and is not what I want.- There is occasionally a situation which causes my screens to both go blank, and it is definitely tied to a condition on some web pages/sites, because when I close those tabs, the screens return to normal. This has happened in both Chrome and Firefox, so it's not tied to one browser, either. I haven't been able to nail down exactly what those conditions are, but if I can, I'll update this review.Other than the above, it's fine, although I find a couple things lacking that would make it a better product:- Supply power through the USB-C port. As it is now, I have to separately power the laptop using the Dell adapter.- Make the USB-C cable longer or provide an extension cable. I would prefer to hide the port replicator unit (and all the cords going into it) under my desk and just have a single cord coming from it, but this isn't possible as it currently is since it's so short (6 to 7 inches, I'd say)

author: Susan
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 16, 2020
content: so i have been having issues with my pc, but until i can do more testing on what i needed to replace i am switching to my laptop. also i use a laptop for work so i wanted to take this opportunity to try a docking station i could use for both.the delivery was fast, and it came in good condition.set up was fat, but the first immediate issue i noticed was the usb-c cable hooking up to the laptop is VERY short, we are talking about 6inches roughly, so all the chords you are connecting to it are sitting super close to the laptops which makes it very messy looking. plus since i am using this for 2 different laptops which of course have the usb-c connections on opposite sides the short connection makes it annoying that i have to move the whole unit just to switch laptops.second issue i found is that at least once a day it becomes super sluggish, and even messes with my monitor set up. what i mean is that i use the laptop screen and 2 external monitors. i have them all extended, and at least once a day it glitches and makes my 2 external monitors mirrored. it becomes super annoying since that means i need to shut down my work just to fix everything.so i am on the fence about returning it at this point =\

author: Kirsten Dobson
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 19, 2022
content: Worked just as expected for the first 6 months. I have two monitors that I connect with HDMI and then also a keyboard and mouse that I used daily with this docking station. About 6 months in my mouse stopped working with it, but everything else still worked so I just plugged it directly into my laptop. A month or so later the USB port for my keyboard also stopped working. Now about 10 months after buying, one of the HDMIs ports for a monitor isn’t working either. So now I need to buy a new docking station as this one really only works to connect one of my monitors.TL;DR: Works great for first 6-ish months before parts stop working one at a time. If you’re fine with potentially having to replace in less than a year, this docking station should be fine.

author: K Boswell
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 19, 2020
content: UPDATE:  The hub has started to get EXTREMELY hot during use, as in it will burn you if touched for more than a second or two hot.  It still works, but this has me lowering my rating.  Also, I received a card in the mail asking me to honestly rate the product and I would be sent a gift card, no matter the rating.  Not surprisingly, that wasn't ever received.ORIGINAL:  As my wife and I began WFH in March of 2020 for COVID, we quickly realized it was going to be too difficult to work off our laptops the entire time, and needed to connect to monitors, USB devices, etc. and the laptops just didn't have enough outputs.  I am extremely happy in how much better things are with this hub, and it has been a great product for us.  The dual HDMI connections let us use both monitors, which is critical for my wife's work.  I can easily switch over to my laptop from the USB C connection when needed, without having to unplug anything.  It simply works.

【Ultra-portable & Compact Powerful Workstation】 You could easily put the docking station in your bag or pocket. The extremely fast 1000M Ethernet port helps gamers and office workers download movies or music faster, transfer files faster, and reduce latency in use.

author: Ramesh
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 25, 2021
content: Have been using this for 2 months now and didnt have any issues and was quite happy.  I have two monitors and the key board dongle connected to this docking station.  For the past 1 week i am experiencing issues with the USB port response where the key board dongle is connected.  it literally stops working in the middle of busy work and irritates. i thought its a problem with the keyboard so change new battery and tried with other keyboards too.  I observed there is no issue when the dongle is connected to my laptop directly.

author: michael
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 27, 2020
content: I really like this product, but it does have a couple of minor issues. 1st the cable that goes from the device into the computer is too short. 2nd, connection is very delicate and it can easily loose connection with the computer (I use a Mac Pro). This can be a real pain especially if you are constantly plugging and unplugging cables into the device.  I had originally purchased this device and returned it because this issue and I thought it was a defected.  then when we received the second order, it had the same issue. We learned to live with it...

author: Donna Labuguen
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 3, 2020
content: I was excited to use the product with my MacBook.  However, the problem I encountered was that it was not even with the laptop(when the device was inserted with the company name on top).  The device sat slightly lower than the MacBook Pro.  Therefore, if you have your laptop on top of a table or anything flat, it will slightly tilt to the right.  My quick fix was to turn the product upside down(now you see the bottom of the adapter) and it works fine.  It kind of bothers me that I'm seeing the bottom of the device.  For the mean time, I will use it because I need it.

author: david martinez
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 24, 2019
content: I am using this with a 2018 macbook pro. This device has three display *ports*, but can only mirror external displays. In other words, this device presents to the computer as a single display. This needs to be much more clearly stated in the language.The description includes this (after boasting of being able to run 3x 1080p displays)  "Attention: OS system doesn’t support Extend mode". This is the only hint I could find that this is *really* a single display device that essentially acts like a splitter.

author: Duece
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 5, 2019
content: DON'T BE FOOLED. This product is a triple MIRROR display, NOT a triple Extended Display. You can only use the two HDMI to Extend the display. If you use the 2 HDMI and the VGA, the VGA mirrors one of the HDMI. To get true Triple Extended Display, this product will not get you there as you will use the two HDMI on the Dock and then use the HDMI on your laptop or a mini/USB converter.

author: lynn garcia
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 30, 2020
content: I purchased this docking station to be able to connect my Surface Book laptop to two additional external monitors. This allowed me to use a total of three screens (laptop included) at once (I haven't tested to see if it supports four). My laptop uses a USB-C port for transmitting visual output.ProsFor the price, you pay you get a variety of USB ports and features. If you are like me and have a laptop that doesn't carry many ports this can be useful.Overall the station doesn't really heat up much at all when just using it for long periods of time and it transitions smoothly once I plug my laptop in.USB-C cord feels solid and not flimsy.No lag between screens.ConsThe material is lightweight and easily slides around on a surface.  I used velcro strips to keep it in place on my desk but I assume you could also use another antislip material.The USB-C cord is short measuring at just over 6 inches. This created some issues for me when trying to position the station on my desk since it had to always be close to the laptop. Additionally, you have to be careful to not bend the cord excessively since it is short and built into the station. If you were to break this cord I'm not sure how much use the rest of the station would be if your laptop uses a USB-C for visual output. (Potentially a USB-C to HDMI might work to resolve this issue or add extra length, however, I haven't tested this theory).Some of the USB ports experience lag when connecting a mouse or keyboard to them. I found that just plugging in directly to my laptop experienced no delay.Summary: Overall for the price you pay the station works smoothly for extending your screen. The lag on some of the ports makes them almost useless at times so if the additional features aren't essential I'd go with a more simplified docking station. If you don't want your station to be right next to your laptop (USB-C input)  I might recommend looking for a more solid docking station and just buying a longer USB-C cord.

author: Dale
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 5, 2020
content: Update: customer service reached out and refunded the full amount.  In addition, they inquired if there were any other remedies they could offer to make things right. Therefore I am updating my review as the product works well but buyers should be aware of the issue that occurs when the computer sleeps as noted previously.Been using this for over a month as a dock for a laptop to connect to dual displays with the lid closed. I quickly realized that every time the computer went to sleep while not in use, when I brought it back online the 2 displays would no longer extend, only duplicate the same thing on both screens. After some troubleshooting i discovered that the dock had to be unplugged from power and the computer and everything plugged back in to get the extend display function to work again.I contacted customer care via email and was told the item was defective and offered a $20 refund (it costs $79).  When I pointed out the original cost, they asked me to return it and they would send a refund.  I proposed they send a new unit and I would return the defective one when it was received. Then they replied that it wasn't actually defective, but that the product does in fact have to be unplugged each time the computer goes into sleep mode so it is working "properly".  If that's true it should have been noted in the description because who wants to unplug everything and plug it back in every time you walk away for a while? I adjusted my power settings somewhat as a workaround but don't want to leave the computer running 24/7 so it is still a problem I have to deal with. Not happy with this product and will be looking for something else that works like common sense would dictate.

author: muddman33
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 23, 2020
content: I purchased this about a year ago but it did not start getting a lot of use till Covid hit and I was remote in April.  I have been remote since then and have used this on my work Dell Precision 3530 laptop.  It worked pretty much error free through September but now it randomly loses my two second HDMI connected monitors.  I have been unable to find a sequence of steps to get them to reconnect consistently.  Sometimes I spend and hour rebooting trying to get it to work.  The two monitors will show on my laptop in display settings but they will not have signal going to them.  Eventually, I will get them to work but it is frustrating.  I am sure my laptop has taken a lot of updates since April but there appear to be no updated drivers for this device.  After just trying for close to an hour I unplugged it and plugged it back in and it just randomly worked.  No really rhyme or reason.  If anyone has the magic formula, please share.  Otherwise, the device is doing what I need when it works.  I have the laptop screen as a monitor along with two HDMI monitors and they extend the screen across all three.  I also have a logitech keyboard and mouse plugged in and they work fine.  I went with with device because the Dell docking stations are probably double the price or more.  Great when it is working!!!!

author: Amber Dixon
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 28, 2022
content: UPDATE: The company has amazing customer service who stand by their product. Obviously from the number of 4-5 star reviews, that not many experience what I did when I connected my devices. So, when they learned about my issue, they reached out to help rectify the issue. That outreach doesn’t happen often with other companies, so I was impressed. For that, I gave them 4 stars. Customer Service tells a lot about a company.While the station had plenty of ports and displayed dual monitors, it glitched so many times that my internet would go out (blamed it on provider, and after many tech visits, learned it was on our end.) It also caused my brand new laptop to reset when I attempted to put it in sleep mode. I also learned that it created power disruption, causing the laptop to think there was problem, making it reset.After 2 weeks of having techs visit my home, and calling Lenovo about the laptop problem, I learned that it was the device.Once I replaced it with another docking station, all problems resolved.

author: Eli Dery
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 8, 2020
content: I bought this as I, like many others, recently found myself working from home. It connected to my Think Pad with no issues, and allows me to connect a keyboard, mouse, cooling fan, and two extra monitors, as well as keep my computer plugged in and charge my headphones, watch, phone, or any other device that needs charging. You do need to use your charging cable with your computer to plug it in to a power source, which makes it a little less convenient if you are taking your computer somewhere you may need your charger, but it is not a big issue. The largest issue that I have come across is that whenever the computer reboots, it doesn't recognize both monitors, instead considers them both the same, until I unplug both monitors, the computer and the power source from the hub, then plug them back in, power, then computer, then the two monitors. This issue was most problematic before I had figured out how to fix the issue, but now is more of a minor inconvenience than anything else. All-in-all, I consider this hub well worth the money, it has worked well every day since early March, and I expect it will continue to for the foreseeable future.TL,DR: Considering this hub is half as expensive as other computer hub devices, and works very well, with only a few hiccups in the three months I have used it, I consider it well worth the money. I have recommended it to many of my coworkers, and I recommend it to you.

author: S.N.
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 19, 2022
content: Update2: Changed my rating to 4 stars.  The seller contacted me for more information which I provided.  They were kind enough to refund my purchase, which was not requested or necessary since I did not return the dock.  Customer service with this seller is very good.Update:  I have been using this doc for about 6 months.  It works well for normal tasks.  However, I have discovered that when I am on a Microsoft Teams call, sharing my screen and running certain programs, the call will drop, my internet will drop out and I am forced to reboot the laptop.I am using a Dell Latitude.  We have 1 gig internet service.  I did not experience this trouble when using a Dell WD19TB dock.This has happened enough times now that I'm pretty sure it's the dock.  Either the ethernet connector or the thunderbolt connector cannot keep up.The connection to my two monitors,  keyboard and mouse have been fine.I wouldn't recommend this to someone who requires a lot of bandwidth for work.

author: Fats Waychee
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 22, 2021
content: I used this device for a year or so without any problem. Then, somehow, something must have propped the device up from below, and at the same time something else muzf have pushed down on the case of my MacBook Pro. The result was that the sockets within my Mac were bent down. That action resulted in the bottom of the computer case being forced out of its clips. The bottom part of the case on that side was no longer flush with the case rim.Since then I tried it on the repaired Max and discovered that it no longer works, so its external contacts probably were bent. I decided to replace it with a similar device ending in a simple plug.If I were going to use this type of adapter, I would adhere some kind of shim on the underside of the adapter so at least pressure applied to the top of the adapter could not bend anything.I recently reactivated an old Macintosh from around 2007 to try to test for some wi-fi problems I was having. I was surprised at how much heavier it was than my current Mac. The saving in weight can mean that things like the outer case thickness becomes too thin to stand up to some accidents.

author: Kelly Chin
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 3, 2020
content: I used this to consolidate all of my USB devices + two external HDMI monitors for my ASUS laptop.  Using two HDMI inputs, it does technically work with three screens as long as you count your laptop as a screen.I also have an old VGA monitor and I decided to try and add it, but it won't really work at all: only mirrors what is on one of the other screens - even if used alone.  It states that this pretty clearly in the instruction manual I received, but I don't see this clearly stated in the Amazon description.  Worse, the amazon pictures show a laptop connected to HDMI1, HDMI2 and VGA without clearly stating that the third external monitor is only going to mirror one of the other ones.  I do see, now that I look back very closely at the picture, that there is a little red x next to one image where it says "extend mode" and seems to be showing this graphically - but they really need to say this in the text somewhere.But overall I am reasonably happy with it.  My various USB peripherals also all work including a printer, keyboard, mouse and drawing pad.  The mouse was a little laggy so I moved it back to a port on the laptop instead, but it was mostly functional using the hub.Last, the incompatible list in the manual (but not the Amazon site) also says "all asus series", but it clearly works on mine (ASUS Zenbook UX533FD i7)

author: Jack W.
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 14, 2020
content: I purchased this docking station as a part of my new home office configuration.  My criteria was functionality, versatility, durability and cost. After much research and reviews I decided on this product. My original goal was just to connect my basic hardware for home office work purposes. That was a laptop and monitor. After having used it and since this year (2020)  and working from home, I've expanded my goals to configure a high productivity power home/work workstation. This includes connecting different devices (laptops, tablet, dual monitors, Bluetooth).  The hub is working well with my configuration and no compatibility issues so far.My hardware:Laptop: Dell and Lenovo  (USB 3.0)Monitors:  Dell Ultrasharp 25"  (HDMI)Table: Samsung Galaxy (USB 3.0)Pros:1) Versatility and usability.2) Price.Cons:1) I didn't have a need for the USB-C power port. At least not yet with the hardware that I have.2) I didn't have need to the VGA port.  Could use for additional USB.3) I don't use SD that much any more.  Could use for additional USB.4) Hub unit does get warm.What I haven't tested yet.1) I haven't tested Ultra-HD/4k action video or video gaming display performance.Wish List:1) Switchable USB ports.Overall, a good hub. I would recommend.

author: Jean
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 4, 2020
content: I have a ASUS Zephyrus GX531GW-AB76 with 2 external monitors (the laptop only has 1 hdmi port)The USB ports are nice. The dual display works most times but I sometimes have to restart the computer a couple of times before I'm able to see both displays at the correct resolution. I'm not sure if it's mostly my computer or not, but we have another Dell computer and it sometimes causes that problem as well.The first one we got was defective and started smoking... and after speaking with customer service, we got it replaced.To get both monitors working, we did need to get an external power source (90w power delivery charger). Without it, the adapter doesn't have enough power and doesn't work. I feel like they should have included an adapter, as the docking station doesn't fully work without one.Overall, I would recommend this. Before purchasing this, you need to make sure your USB C supports displays and is plugged into the correct one. My laptop has 2 USB C ports, 1 supports display, another doesn't - and the docking station only works on the one that supports display. Likewise, we bought another one for someone else, and realized after the fact that his USB port does not support display.

author: Michael
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 10, 2020
content: I was skeptical because it says doesn't work with Acers. Then as I did more researcher none if them claim to work with acers. So I took a chance and it works well with my predator laptop. I have two monitors, keyboard, mouse, audio interface and webcam and it works flawlessly for the most part.The only part I find annoying is that if for some reason something happens to where you lose communication with a device a lot of times in order for it to work again you have to restart or turn off you computer and unplug the hub while its rebooting. This was a huge pain in the but when I had a program crash.  It stopped recognizing  both monitors as separate.  It would display to both of them, but windows couldn't detect them as 1 and 2 so it just mirrored. Finally after a lot of digging and there being hardly any information on their website I came back to the product page on amazon and found the turn it off and unplug it trick. Sounds pretty basic, but I tried just plane old restarting and it didn't work because I didn't unplug it. This has happened to me twice now. Second time I restarted the computer and unplugged it as it booted up and worked just fine after plugging it back in.

author: REGENIA WARD
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 7, 2019
content: I purchased this USB-C/dongle to serve as an adapter for my many USB peripherals. The first thing I noticed was how light it was and all the different ports it had to be so light. It comes with a duster bag where you can easily use it for on the go. I have used the micro SD and the regular one. You can't however use them simultaneously. I did read that the new generation of the Ipad Pros can also hook up but not Thunderbolt (the instructions for this one does state not compatible but someone did connect using an adapter) I have a 2011 Mac Book Air and it DOES NOT work with this one but it did work on my son's Mac Book Pro. I transferred pics from my camera and it was very fast. The HDMI worked flawlessly on the Mac Book Pro. I used all the ports except for the Ethernet (no need) this dongle does so much and well worth it. I would definitely recommend this to a friend. So the only con for me was the SD card since I was going back and forth with the pictures and that this particular one isn't compatible with my laptop or iPad Pro. It does however offer 8 compatible laptops but mine is just an old model. So if you have a Mac Book Pro 2016-2018 and a Mac Book 2015-2018, this one is for you.

author: TreatsfortheSweet
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 12, 2019
content: I bought this to connect to my HP Spectre x360, primarily to interface with two monitors. At first, I could not figure out how to make both monitors display independently, and I was quite miffed because product features advertised triple display (solution below). I spent an hour on the phone with Amazon product support - completely incompetent - and attempted to reach the manufacturer several times. After scouring the internet for a solution, to no avail, I stumbled upon the solution...and it's so simple. Originally, I had both HDMI plugged into the two available ports, and the laptop power supply plugged into the hub as well (as opposed to directly to the laptop). The hub was then plugged into the laptops 'primary' usbc thunderbolt (i.e. the usbc that would most obviously be used for power). The fix? Once I plugged the port in the 'secondary' usb c thunderbolt, everything worked fine! Don't know if I was just being a dunce, but the customer service experience left me in a sour mood. Other than that, but product worked as advertised so 4 stars. I will echo sentiments about heat, as well as the integrated usbc dongle. It's annoying to have a fixed length of cord/orientation for that part, as it restricts options for availability of setup.

content: This multi-port adapter serves the purpose but has some minor drawbacks: must take the back cover off your Macbook to plug the unit in; the unit is not firmly attached to the Macbook, so if you insert/remove a USB/thumb drive/dongle/HDMI to your bigger screens, the adapter may come out and everything needs to reconnect/reboot. author: Cody j Bird
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 15, 2020
content: I am able to get the usb ports to work successfully, but the displays both 2x HDMI and VGA outputs will not display and I get an error when plugged into the USB c port that "USB Device Not Recognized" the last USB device you connected malfunctioned and Windows does not recognize it. Recommendation Try reconnecting the device. If windows still does not recognize it, your device may not be working properly. I have tried these suggestions and rebooted after connecting. I also have looked for drivers for this usb c hub without success. the site offers a download button for the driver, but it takes you back to the product page. If I can't get the displays to work I will be forced to return. Otherwise I think the device is well designed and other than the connection of mouse and keybaord being slow after connecting the hub I would be happy with the hub.**Update**The company took care of me very well after finding that the USB C port on my HP 850 G3 was USB C Basic. Check your PC that it is not USB C Basic if it is not listed as supported by UtechSmart.

author: R. Edwards
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 20, 2019
content: I am using this for a dock for my MBP 15" 2019 when working from home.  For the most part, it works exactly as described.  I can plug my power supply into this dock, along with my keyboard and mouse, HDMI to one screen and connect to the MBP and all will work.  The only drawback (which was not called out by the company's descriptions) is that you cannot drive two different monitors with different desktop displays (extended desktop) at the same time.  If you plug in a second HDMI connection, it will only mirror.  If you plug in a VGA connection, it also only mirrors, but also reduces the HDMI output to showing only VGA resolution.When at work, I am using the OWC 12 in 1 dock as it can support multiple monitors (Display Port for 1 and TB3 for the other).  It however is considerably more expensive.  Since my company wouldn't pay for the more expensive dock for home, the UTech hub was a reasonable compromise.  I just use a TB3->HDMI adapter and plug it into the MBP separately for a second monitor.

author: Ash G
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 6, 2020
content: This adapter is great. I was really frustrated with apple, and the "no Ports" thing on their new MacBook. I really needed a dongle. All the other dongles, were heavy, had long and messy cables to organize, and were extremely expensive. This dongle is lightweight, so I just keep it attached ti may laptop at all times, so I don't have to go digging in some bad to find it. It is also very slim, and has a compact footprint, so it docent add much thickness to my laptop. It is very easy to use. Just plug it in directlly to the two USB C ports on the side of your MacBook. And, if you have the base model, w/ only 2 ports, the dongle has a usb-c port built in, so you won't need to take it off for charging. It is also far cheaper than apples. Apple is selling one dongle, with penny a lighting porter 40$. This one only cost 16.00. However, I do find it pricey for the aftermarket dongle. other aftermarket dongles are cheaper than this, running a max of 12.00$. I think its totally worth it.

author: Ian M.
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 4, 2021
content: I bought this after the cable from my old dongle split and the wires became frayed. I knew I didn't want another dongle that "dangles" from a cable, so I bought this one, which firmly connected to the side of my MacBook. It felt like a quality, solidly-built device, and the look of it is nice, too. It matches the look of my MacBook. Ultimately, I decided to return it due to lacking an HDMI port, which is crucial to me since I connect my laptop to a larger monitor when working at my desk, but it was my fault for not looking closely at the specifications before buying: I mistakenly thought the USB 2.0 port at the top was an HDMI port.If I didn't need an HDMI hookup, I would definitely have kept this product and would recommend it to others if the ports on this product match their needs. Just be sure to look carefully before buying!

author: Crystal W.
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 20, 2020
content: I bought this product to use with my Dell work laptop so that I could have 3 screens. When I tried to plug in both monitors to both hdmi ports on the docking station, one of the monitors complained that the hertz level was incompatible. I plugged one of the hdmi monitor cables into my laptop, then the other into the docking station. After configuration of display properties to extend my desktop across the 3 displays and making the middle monitor my primary, everything looks great.One thing that I had an issue with was the USB 3.0 ports. There must be a power limit because when using to charge an ecig battery via USB, it got too hot, then everything plugged into the docking station shut down and docking station monitor went black. I unplugged from USB C port on laptop, then replugged back in and everything came back on. For any lower powered USB devices, it works fine without issue.One thing I would change is making the USB C cable to docking station longer.

date: Reviewed in the United States on December 4, 2020
content:
The media could not be loaded.
                



All of my external items that plug into my computer seem to work fine with this hub.  I currently have two monitors plugged in through HDMI, a document camera plugged in through USB, a printer plugged in through USB, and an external keyboard plugged in through USB. I understand most people would have their laptop laying flat on their desk but because I use my laptop as a CPU at school, it has to be propped up higher to be a third monitor.  This leaves me with no place to put the hub.

author: Rhonda Mazone
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 18, 2020
content: This was a great product for the amount of money I paid for it. I was able to connect two monitors and a laptop. The only drawback is that when I restart, I have to disconnect the docking station in order for it to recognize the two monitors. However, this may be a fault of my own. Other than that, I will purchase this product again.  NOTE: I have two monitors, laptop, wired mouse, wired keyboard and a charging cord for my cell phone. I wish I had the ability to connect one more monitor. But I’m not handicapped by it. This was still a great investment.

author: Andre Lagrange
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 7, 2021
content: This was a remarkably compact port expansion hub, about the size of a standard mouse.  I have been able to connect  2 additional monitors, 2 external hard drives, a LAN line and wireless keyboard.  Unlike a previous reviewer,  I had no trouble hooking up both a VGA and HDMI monitor to my laptop, thereby providing  a total of 3 independent screens  The connections are fast, without any notable decrement in functionality for the peripherals mentioned above.The only downsides are that there is no screws to lock the VGA in place (so it tend to become disconnected) and the charging function is significantly slower than just plugging in the power cord.

author: Claribel
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 5, 2020
content: I found this product to be a good product for it's price.  It provided what I needed initially.  It gave me an opportunity to be able to take a MacBook Air and have additional ports that I did not have with the laptop.  Unfortunately, I was using both USB-c's to connect the port to and the port only gave me one additional USB-c port thereby losing one to the device.  I needed to connect an external monitor and needed to purchase another port that provided me the ability to connect to just one USB-c port and use the other for computer power.  If I didn't need the additional monitor, this device would have been more than sufficient for my needs.
