author: Rosemary
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 17, 2020
content: Being a MacBook user, you might have noticed the new USB-c ports and the lack of USB and other ports. This product is a MUST for connecting devices with USB wires. It comes with plenty of charging ports and an SD card port. It's easily accessible and is travel size. However, I have to take my laptop case off for the dongle to be completely inserted in the USB-C port. Another downside is that my computer will start to overhear after a little while with only one port being used.  I am overall satisfied with this product because I can plug in a lot of my devices if I need to transfer data or charge my devices. I would not recommend keeping a device plugged in for too long because your computer will start to overhear and work slow.

author: Marita
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 15, 2020
content: This multi-port adapter is very portable and great for traveling. The 3-USB ports is especially helpful. The only issue I've been having is that I do a lot of traveling and I have a top and bottom shell on my MacBook Pro for protection. So, the two prong C adapter to my Mac doesn't go in all the way so I have to remove the bottom shell. I tried to turn the adapter the other way, but it's the same issue with the top cover clearance. It's no big deal for me to remove the covering but it would be really nice if the prongs where just slightly longer (1/32 or 1/16" to clear that added space needed). Other than that, I love the portability . If you don't have a protective cover, you shouldn't have any problem!

author: Qi Zhao
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 26, 2020
content: I got a hub of the same brand before, but it only supported external monitor. After I got two external monitors, I switched to this product. I tried other products, but they didn't work out for me.pros: The setup is effortless: simply connect the usb-c to my pixelbook, connect the power and the two hdmi cables to my external monitors. Then the monitors can be configured through display setting. The whole process took less than 10 mins for me. I'm also able to connect the mouse and keyboard to the hub, which is necessary as my pixel book doesn't have extra usb ports!cons: maybe a little pricy, but if you get more monitors, maybe it's worth more the price.

content: I absolutely can not work from just my laptop screen so I'm always attached to a couple monitors (or 4 lol). author: Scott
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 1, 2020
content: I am using UtechSmart Multiport USB C  Hub as a work-from-home docking station for my laptop, a new Lenovo IdeaPad 5, an external monitor, and an Anker 6 port USB charging hub.  The Multiport connects to the laptop via the USB-C port, and connects to the external monitor via the Multiport HDMI port.  My mouse and audio headset are plugged into the Multiport's  USB 2.0 ports.  Using the Multiport as a docking station this way allows quick setup for my workspace, only requiring a single connection to my laptop.  I have not tested the USB 3.0 port speeds yet.The Multiport gets a bit warm when in use, which is of a bit of concern, but I keep it well ventilated for heat dissipation.

date: Reviewed in the United States on July 29, 2019
content: This is a great product that allows users to have both a laptop and desktop when connected to the UtechSmart docking station. I keep a small laptop (with the keys covered to keep out dust) and the dock hidden behind two 23” monitors. author: AMC
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 24, 2020
content: [Updated 2021/10/02 to reflect a possible product change:I bought another of this exact model for someone else to use.  It works just as well as the original, but the ethernet adapter chip is now an ASIX AX88179.  It works just fine, and neither I nor the user have noticed any problems with it, but I wanted to make that info available just in case it is important to a potential purchaser.  I'm assuming the reason for the change was a lack of component availability, but I have no way of knowing for certain.  ]I'm going to go into a fair bit of detail in this review.  I get questions about Type C hubs generally, and about a UTechSmart 6-in-1 that I bought last year (when people see me using it with my Pocket 2).  I use that hub just about every day and it has been very reliable.  So like that one, I thought if I put everything into a review I can just point people to it in the future.TL;DR:This hub packs a lot of features into a small package.  As a result this is a complex device composed of multiple chips from different vendors, and it may not behave as you initially expect.  Any device like this is going to have this characteristic.  If you need two separate 4k displays, or a 4k display and any other display, then you may want to consider the newer version of this item instead.  It does dual (extended) 1080p60 well.  If your needs fit within its capabilities, it is a good choice.  Personally, I'm really happy with it, and will probably keep it connected in my office.Design and Use Philosophy:This is also a class of device that can be described as 'jack of all trades, master of none.'  Whether you take it with you or leave it on a desk, it is very useful to have only one cable that handles everything.  But the trade off for that capability is that a single cable has to handle all of the power and data requirements for those functions. Personally, I think this is a worthy trade-off for having all these features in a single device with a single (non proprietary!) cable.  I also think it's a good value at this price.Construction:It is of the same design as the previous 6 in 1 hub, though about 50% larger.  It has a seamless extruded aluminum shell that has either been anodized or has some kind of light PVD coating.  I'm not expert enough to be confident that I can tell the difference by feel.  I can say that it doesn't scratch easily.  Over the last 8 months I haven't exactly babied the previous hub from this manufacturer, and it still looks brand new.  It comes with a simple fabric carry bag, which seems kinda pointless unless you really care about scratches.  I doubt I'll bother using the bag for the new hub.  The aluminum shell seems to do a good job of conducting heat.  It stays at about 38-40 C without any noticeable hot spots.  I haven't tried to open it.  The cable insulation seems to strike a good balance between flexibility and stiffness.  It bends well enough that cable tension doesn't pull the hub around.  I'm not worried that the cable will be damaged from kinking when I just toss it into a bag with other stuff.  This was initially a concern since the cable is permanently attached.USB Type C has many optional features and interconnections with other standards (USB 3.2, Thunderbolt 3, Power Delivery, DisplayPort, upcoming USB 4) to the point that trying to figure out compatibility and capability can be intimidating.  Many parts of the spec are optional.  The extra hardware added to this device can have its own issues or interactions with the above-mentioned standards.A Type C connection has four high-speed serial links, or 'lanes' plus a legacy USB 2.0 connection.  The lanes can be used for different functions.  USB 3.1 Gen 1 requires two lanes.  Faster modes (not supported by this hub) use all four.  Some other video output devices use all four lanes, leaving only USB 2.0 for everything else.  There are other pins in the connector for power, etc.This is a USB 3.1 Gen 1 (Via Labs VL817) device, so 5 Gb/s bandwidth is shared between the USB ports, the Ethernet port (Realtek RTL8153), and the SD card reader (USB 2.0).  Some Type C hubs will use the dedicated USB 2.0 channel for the USB 2 ports instead of just hanging them off the internal USB 3.1 hub.  I don't know if this device does that, and if it can it may require host device support to do it.The device uses the remaining two lanes for video out via Multi-Stream Transport (MST).  MST is a DisplayPort standard that allows multiple displays to be multiplexed into one DP data stream.  So each display is driven by your GPU.  There are no DisplayLink chips in this hub.  Ignore the graphic on the product page showing the display chip is a LX9823.  I contacted the manufacturer, and they told me that it uses a Synaptics VMM3332BJG.  This chip takes in a DisplayPort 1.2a MST signal and can output one DP 1.2/DP++, one HDMI 1.4b, and one VGA port (mirrored).  DP++ (aka dual-mode) is a DisplayPort mode that basically changes the output pins to match the HDMI spec.  DP++ ver. 1.1 can output up to 4k30.  So I think that this one chip is handling all three outputs without any other intermediaries.  Only having two lanes for video means that the available bandwidth is half what it would normally be for a given data rate.  DisplayPort has different data rates in the spec.  When two DP devices are connected, they attempt to connect at the fastest speed they can both support over the cable between them, and fall back to slower ones if needed.  The fastest data rate supported by DisplayPort 1.2 is HBR2.Testing:Laptops (year, cpu, gpu, os)(OS up to date, latest drivers, etc.):GPD Pocket 2 (2018, m3-8100y, uhd 615, Win10 LTSC 1809)LG Gram 15 (2016, i7-6500u, hd 520, Win 10 Home 1909)Lenovo Thinkpad E495 (2019, Ryzen 7 3700u, Vega 10, Win 10 Pro 1909)Displays (native res):Dell W3706MC (768p)Dell S2240L(1080p)Dell U2713HM (1440p)Samsung UN50NU6950 (4K)Display Testing (tl;dr:Cannot have two 4k30 displays in extend mode):According to the DisplayPort spec, MST allows the displays to have different resolutions.  Testing with the above laptops on the above monitors, I could connect one display at 4k30, or one display at 1440p60, or two displays at 1080p60, or two displays with one 1080p60 and one 768p60.  When I connected one display at 4k or 1440 and plugged in a second 1080 display, the first display dropped down to 1080p60.  This behavior is consistent across all three laptops.  This limitation is documented in both the product page and the manual where they state the it supports single or duplicate 4k30 on Macbooks but only a single 4k30 on Windows.  While both HDMI ports can technically output 4k30, you will not be able to have a true dual 4k30 display (i.e. in extended mode).Warning, math:The DP alt-mode on this hub only has two lanes, since the hub reserves the other two high-speed lanes for USB 3.1.  So with HBR2 there is 8.64 Gb/s throughput after overhead is removed.  This is enough for one 4k30 (6.2 Gb/s), one 1440p60 (5.6 Gb/s) or two 1080p60 (2x3.2 Gb/s).  This matches the behavior I have observed: I can plug in one display and get full resolution, but as soon as I plug in the second (1080p) the first display drops to 1080p as well.  At least it falls back gracefully and doesn't just stop working or something.One of the laptops I have tested it with is an AMD Ryzen with a Vega iGPU, and the AMD driver software reports the link speed as 5.4 Gbps x 2 lanes.  This matches HBR2's raw data rate (incl. overhead). I don't know how to see the DisplayPort link speed when using an intel iGPU (Intel Graphics Command Center, latest version), so I can't check those.  I don't have any computers with both a nvidia gpu and a Type C port.  Testing this is difficult, since I'm not sure how to monitor the link speed. The hub would need to be able to connect at HBR3 to support 2x4k30 displays in extended mode (12.96 Gb/s throughput to support 2x6.2 Gb/s displays). I assume that this link rate is only between the laptop's type C port and the hub's MST chip.  I'm assuming that once the chip demuxes the datastream and converts it to HDMI, the link rate is no longer a concern.  I'm making several assumptions here, and could easily be wrong.  I'm learning as I go.  Another way one might generally get higher performance over DisplayPort is to use ver 1.4 or higher devices that support Display Stream Compression.  Since this hub is a DP 1.2 device, it doesn't support that.DisplayPort alt-mode over USB Type C is part of the 1.4 spec, so one might assume that it should support the HBR3 data rate.  But this is an optional part of the specification, and it not required.Everything else about the hub performs as advertised, and the various video capabilities are well documented for a device at this price point.VGA:VGA output was as good as can be expected when pushed to 1080p.  It was crisp and readable, but not as sharp as a digital signal (it never is).  If the vga cable housing is oversize it may block the Ethernet port, but most cables won't do so.Ethernet (RTL8153):The latest drivers from Realtek really help with stability under max load.  Don't just use whatever driver Windows auto-installs for you.  With the right drivers, this chip is a solid performer, saturating a gigabit connection under Windows.USB ports:It has two USB 3.1 gen 1 and two USB 2.0 ports.  All testing was done while the hub was also connected to one or more displays.I ran speed tests on usb3 with a couple different sata3 ssds in a generic USB adapter.  Each disk performed as fast when connected to the hub as when directly connected to a laptop's usb port.  Since the hub's USB controller always has two lanes assigned to it, I'd expect full performance at all times, regardless of how many displays are also connected.SD card reader test (USB 2.0)I tested a Sandisk SDSQXA1-256G-GN6MA, which can do 161 MB/s read and 76 MB/s write when using a Sandisk Mobilemate reader.  (Some Sandisk readers will run at a faster speed than the standard UHS104 if the card supports it.)  I need not have bothered using my fastest card to test, as the reader seems to only use USB 2.0.  It tested at 30MB/s write and 40 MB/s read.  The reader reports that it is USB 3 capable, but doesn't connect at that speed.  I have another card that I like to test readers with, as for some reason half the card readers I own refuse to see it.  It is a Sandisk Extreme 60MB/s SD card.  The hub's reader saw it every time.Documentation:The included manual is actually pretty good, and is up front about the hub's capabilities and limitations incl. device incompatibilities.Triple display is kind of a stretch here, since the third output is a mirror.  But I don't consider it deceptive, since the Mfr. is very up front about this limitation and includes examples in the manual, product page, and product images for all different video output configurations.Power consumption:The manual states 8W is consumed by the hub, with a max of 87W input, leaving up to 75W for pass-through @14.5-20V.  I couldn't test this part, I don't have a laptop that charges faster than 60w over USB C.  I tested the hub's consumption with a Type C in-line power meter while powering the hub from the laptop.1.8W with one display connected.3.3W with one display and ethernet.There was a negligible power increase with a second display or while transferring files over ethernet.  So I think the 8W official power consumption is including the max power available to USB devices plugged into the hub.  So be careful with how much you plug in at once, just as with a regular un-powered USB hub.  Even while there is a power adapter plugged in to the hub.I also tested how much power it would pass through to the host laptop.  I tested this using the Lenovo laptop listed above and the factory power adapter.  When plugged directly into the laptop, it charged at 60W.  When the hub was used, total power drawn from the adapter fell to 55W.  Odd.  Here's the layout:AC adapter -> power meter -> hub -> laptop.I don't have the equipment to test further, and a sample size of one isn't exactly definitive.Conclusion (Congrats to you if you actually read this far!):It's a good value for the price, if you need the features it provides.  It can work well as a desk-bound docking station or as a travel adapter.  Make sure that the feature set will match your needs, as there are other hubs out there with different capabilities.  If you need fewer features and more portability, this manufacturer's 6 in 1 hub is both smaller and cheaper.  If you need more or higher resolution video output you may want to look for a device that uses a newer version of the DisplayPort spec, such as the updated version mentioned below.Updated version:Ironically, as I was writing this review I noticed that the manufacturer has just introduced an updated version (12-in-1) with 3 HDMI outputs.  One of the graphics shows a VMM5310 and a VMM3332.  The VMM5310 is a newer Synaptics video interface chip that supports a DP 1.4 (HBR3) input, a DP 1.4/DP++ output, and two HDMI 2.0b outputs.  I'm assuming the DP output is connected to the input of the VMM3332, and that chip just converts it to HDMI.  That design could also work without the VMM3332 at all if the third HDMI port is run using the DP++ mode of the VMM5310.  So there may be a limitation with designing it that way.  If the laptop or other device that you plan to use with this hub only supports DP 1.2, there is less reason to buy the updated hub, since you won't be able to use the higher data rates anyway.  Your best bet at that point would be to buy a hub that uses all four lanes for video, instead of just two.

author: lynn garcia
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 30, 2020
content: I purchased this docking station to be able to connect my Surface Book laptop to two additional external monitors. This allowed me to use a total of three screens (laptop included) at once (I haven't tested to see if it supports four). My laptop uses a USB-C port for transmitting visual output.ProsFor the price, you pay you get a variety of USB ports and features. If you are like me and have a laptop that doesn't carry many ports this can be useful.Overall the station doesn't really heat up much at all when just using it for long periods of time and it transitions smoothly once I plug my laptop in.USB-C cord feels solid and not flimsy.No lag between screens.ConsThe material is lightweight and easily slides around on a surface.  I used velcro strips to keep it in place on my desk but I assume you could also use another antislip material.The USB-C cord is short measuring at just over 6 inches. This created some issues for me when trying to position the station on my desk since it had to always be close to the laptop. Additionally, you have to be careful to not bend the cord excessively since it is short and built into the station. If you were to break this cord I'm not sure how much use the rest of the station would be if your laptop uses a USB-C for visual output. (Potentially a USB-C to HDMI might work to resolve this issue or add extra length, however, I haven't tested this theory).Some of the USB ports experience lag when connecting a mouse or keyboard to them. I found that just plugging in directly to my laptop experienced no delay.Summary: Overall for the price you pay the station works smoothly for extending your screen. The lag on some of the ports makes them almost useless at times so if the additional features aren't essential I'd go with a more simplified docking station. If you don't want your station to be right next to your laptop (USB-C input)  I might recommend looking for a more solid docking station and just buying a longer USB-C cord.

author: KM70
date: Reviewed in the United States on October 8, 2020
content: UPDATED REVIEW:I have updated my review from 3 to 5 stars. Here is why:1) customer service is above and beyond. I wrote about my original product (released about 5 months ago and had some issues. The techs immediately contacted me and made it right. A newer model was sent for no cost and no shipping which resolved all of the issues I had with the first one that was seemingly incompatible with newer software updates. This one - no issues.2) the newest model release is running with no issues. The unit does not get hot anymore and it is recognized automatically update computer update and restart without having to unplug and plug back in.3) the dual HDMI connections are instantly recognized.4) no more quirky disconnects on the new version.HIGHLY RECOMMEND THIS HUB. GREAT FOR CONTINUAL AT HOME USE AS WELL AS TRAVEL. 2 HIGHSPEED USB PORTS AS WELL THAT WORK LIKE A DREAM FOR DATA TRANSFER. IF YOU HAVE A CHOICE BETWEEN AN EARLIER RELEASE AND NEW ONE, GET THE NEW ONE.AND SHOUT OUT TO ANNIE, GOT THE JOB DONE. BEST CS EXPERIENCE YET.OLD REVIEW NOW UPDATED: I purchased this hub because I needed to connect two HDMI monitors to my laptop. I debated between this and a docking station, and after 4 months of use, I think I am going to get a docking station instead. The reason being the following: 1) if the computer restarts (due to updates or whatever), the USB C hub is not recognized and I have to unplug, wait about 20 seconds and plug it back in again and wait for my monitors to be recognized all over. sometimes this does not happen on the first try. 2) There is not sufficient wattage to charge an iPhone adequately and many times the iPhone will not recognize the device 3) if the thing gets bumped, it "disconnects" from the laptop and needs to be unplugged and reset 4) it does get fairly warm to hot with continuous running which is worrisome. This is probably best used for travel as a USB extender in a pinch, but not a long term solution to multiple monitor desk setup long term.

author: Rachel T.
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 25, 2019
content: I received this item in return for my honest review, so here it is...I am a heavy tech user and have several devices I carry with me on a daily basis. My MacBook Air, my Nikon DSLR camera, my iPhone 8+, multiple battery packs, and this does not include all of my son's devices (he's as bad as I am). I do not use the Ethernet so I have no use for that particular port, but I definitely use the USB, SD cards, and other multiple ports (all at the same time sometime!!).The first thing I want to mention are the aesthetics (not that that is what's important). The hub is encased in an aluminum material that is very sturdy and seems as though it will withstand a lot of wear and tear. The multiple ports are placed on the sides and around the perimeter with a nice bit of spacing between each to accommodate multiple plugs being used side by side. It also comes with a nice little velvet pouch to keep it stored when not in use, or to transport and prevent it from being scratched. I leave the permanent cord on the end sticking out of the pouch so as not to scratch the hub's casing.With this device, I can download pictures/video from my nikon, charge a phone or battery pack, import pictures from sd cards, etc... all at the same time. The only thing you have to look out for is the hub does tend to get pretty warm with multiple things going on at the same time.So far, so good! I recommend purchasing this if you are a high tech user and need multiple ports for multiple devices at the same time. This is compact and small, and easily transportable. This makes traveling with your devices so much easier and more convenient. This particular one is a little pricier than others listed on Amazon, but they also offer an 18 month guarantee/warranty by either refund or replacement. This definitely would give me peace of mind about spending this amount of money!

author: PhoenixM
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 19, 2022
content: I'm honestly surprised that this hub has 60% 5-star reviews.I (IT guy) bought this to go along with a brand new Dell Latitude 5520 (Win 10x64) for my boss, so as to give him additional ports and fewer things to plug/unplug every day. It has not performed as expected.1. It has two HDMI ports, but if you plug a monitor into both of them, the computer locks up (not a BSoD; simply frozen and unresponsive). The only way to unfreeze it when this happens is to unplug the hub itself, i.e. even unplugging the second monitor from the hub does not unfreeze it. Note that having one monitor plugged into the hub and one monitor plugged into the laptop's onboard HDMI port is fine; it's just two on the hub simultaneously that doesn't seem to work.2. The RJ-45 Ethernet port loses connection for a minute or two multiple times per day. This problem doesn't happen when using the laptop's on-board RJ-45 port. And there's nothing in the network's DHCP logs suggesting lease renegotiation issues or anything like that; the port on the hub is simply losing connectivity for unknown reasons.Price was one of the determining factors when I made the purchase, and clearly we got what we paid for.Edit (2024-Jan-02): A coworker bought one of these also, in late 2022, and also had trouble with the network connection dropping. He told me at that time that he had contacted the manufacturer, and they sent him a replacement free of charge. I happened to stop by his office last month, and noticed that he was VPNed into the network via wi-fi, and not connected to Ethernet; when I asked him about it, he said that the Ethernet port on the replacement hub was also unable to maintain a reliable, consistent connection.So that's three separate hubs with a bad Ethernet port, folks. Make of that what you will.

author: T. Young
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 21, 2020
content: DISCLAIMER:I had bought a USB-C hub from UtechSmart in the past and they offered me this device for free if I would write a review of the device. So you can take my review with a 'grain of salt' if you wish, but I'm being completely honest in my review (if it was a piece of junk I would say so).With that disclaimer out of the way.This is a nice USB-C hub.The other version I bought was UCN3273.That version has 3 USB3 ports, 1 USB-C port (also Power Delivery), 1 HDMI port, and one Gigabyte NIC.This version, UCN3270 has 2 USB3 ports, 2 USB2 ports (marked with mouse/keyboard so you aren't using up the USB3 ports for peripherals), 2 HDMI ports, 1 VGA port, 1 USB-C port (also Power Delivery), one Gigabyte NIC, and microSD/SD slots.There is a note in the User Manual that you cannot use BOTH SD slots at the same time. Probably not a big deal for most people and I should note that the cards stick out so you would not want to transport cards in this hub. There are also limitations on using all 3 video ports that are explained in the User Guide, suffice it today that you would only want to use this hub for dual monitors (besides your laptop monitor). There are also some notes in the User Guide about incompatibility with a few devices.I plugged the hub into a Microsoft Surface Go computer using this neat little device:https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0816PV1YZ/If your USB-C port is on the base of your laptop you probably wouldn't need such a device, but the Surface Go has the port on the screen since it's technically a table also (keyboard disconnects). Using that device allows the hub to sit flat on a desktop. I saw now performance degradation from using the connector. NOTE that a Microsoft Surface Go has ONLY 1 USB-C port, no other USB ports. So a hub like this is really nice to have if you are doing anyone 'real' work on the computer.Performance:I plugged in a network cable and disabled my wireless connection, then plugged in a USB3 flash drive and an HDMI monitor. I did not use the Power Delivery feature on this hub, but I have on the lessor hub and it works flawlessly, so I have no doubt it would on this hub also. You WILL need to use the Power Delivery port if you are running 2 monitors. I think I was pushing the limit of USB-C with what I had hooked up, but if functioned well.I then proceeded to fire up a couple Bitorrent downloads, a couple of LARGE file downloads, and playing a streaming video on YouTube.AND while all that was going on, I transferred a couple large files (more than 30GB) from the Surface to my local network storage. So about 2Mb/sec download plus video streaming and an average of 110Mb/sec upload over an extended period.Results?Everything worked fine.I did notice very-very-small 'hiccups' in the streaming video playback from YouTube (almost unnoticeable) while the large files were moving out to my network storage, but once that file transfer completed, the hiccups were no longer present.Probably one of the best considerations of this hub over the lessor hub is heat generation. The lessor hub becomes extremely warm, enough so that I wouldn't set it down on my wooden desktop, but instead would make sure it was sitting on something metal to allow heat dissipation.This newer/better hub gets warm, but not to the point where I would worry about it burning either a wooden desk or the hands of a small child that might pick it up out of curiosity.This hub (UCN3270) is larger than the UCN3273 hub, obviously because it has more connections, which may be a negative in some people's minds. It also costs more. BUT it has better thermal management AND gives you the option to run 2 monitors. I also like that it has 2 USB2 ports if you need to plug in a mouse or keyboard that won't take up precious USB3 ports.So this hub will be the one I keep in my Surface Go bag for traveling, just not sure what I will do with the smaller/lesser hub. :-)

author: SlushierCashew
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 16, 2019
content: I was skeptical about this product at first, given the seemingly complex nature of all the functions they put into it (dual HDMI, networking, fast charging, USB ports, card readers, YIKES!) - but, after a few days of HEAVY use and testing, I can verify that this hub is, in fact, the real deal.  So much so that I am tossing my SD card reader, old USB hub, HDMI splitter, network adapter, AND charger for my HP spectre 360 and switching to just this.PROS:1.  Small.  It's VERY small, particularly impressive given everything that's crammed into it.2.  Quality feel.  It has a high quality feel, too, nice and solid without the usual cheap plastic feel of similiar products being sold these days.  The ports are all rock solid, no wiggle, and plugs & memory cards click firmly into place.3.  Speeds are verified.  USB 2.0 and 3.0 speeds match specs.  This is actually quite rare in USB hubs, even high-priced models from more recognized brands.  The speeds even seem to hold up during multi-card transfers (IE, copying data from an SD card, USB 2.0 stick, AND USB 3.0 external HDD simultaneously - something I do pretty frequently).  As a professional photographer, this kind of speed actually makes a difference in my workflow, and enables me to simultaneously copy photos off my card and back them up to an external HDD at full speed.4. Warranty.  This little wonder has a 12-month warranty, and I actually know from experience that utechsmart stands behind their warranties (they will usually just ship you a new one, very few questions asked).5.  HDMI outs.  I plug my HP Spectre 360 into this, and BAM, I am outputting on two monitors.  SO COOL.  I cannot verify the 4K nature of the HDMI ports, but it definitely works at 1080P without a problem.CONS:1.  Price.  It is a little expensive for what, at first, appears to be "just" a USB hub - BUT, if you use this as intended (to replace a docking station for something like a HP Spectre 360), you will see that it is SO much more than just a USB hub and also VERY reasonably priced.  If you are looking for just a USB hub, there are definitely cheaper options.2. Temperature.  It gets pretty hot during use, especially when charging the laptop and using 2 monitors simultaneously.  Not sure if this will affect the long term effectiveness of the unit.3.  SD card speed.  While the USB ports definitely transfer files at full spec speed, the SD card reader is linked to the USB 2.0 bus and is therefore slower than you might expect.  If you need faster SD card transfers, find a USB 3.0 SD card dongle and plug it into this unit's USB 3.0 port.So that's about it.  Great little unit!  Highly recommended, if you are in a position to use all the features.  Of course, they also make smaller units with less/different features, so check out their full lineup to find something that might meet your needs a little better (if this one doesn't).

author: AMZing Kristen
date: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2021
content: I just started a new job. I actually had to set up to home offices because we live in two locations. My new company sent me a Dell Latitude 5410 and my previous computer’s Dell docking station did not work with this new computer. I was genuinely shocked when I found out how much a new Dell docking station would cost for my new computer, so I began to research other options. I came across this Utech Smart Triple Display USB and decided for the price, I would give it a shot. I could get both of the docking stations I needed from UtechSmart for less than one Dell.This docking station is everything I needed. There is a reason they have 2509 reviews and are averaging 4.5 stars. This docking station does more than the comparable Dell one at a fraction of the cost.I did have one small hiccup when I was trying to hook It up. I kept getting an error that said that my laptop did not have “enough power to power the accessory.” Some computers do not have to have a power source directly connected to the docking station, but for my dell I did need power  connected directly to the docking station. My laptop came with the traditional M9 charger that most Dells come with. I purchased a USB-C charger, and plugged it directly into my UTech docking station, and was then able to get my Laptop working with the Utech docking station.I have been using the docking station every day since 12/31/20 with no issues. The docking station is slim and feels durable. It is small and compact, but it has so many different kinds of ports!Save yourself some money, and buy this instead of an OEM docking station!

author: venkateswarlu gopavarapu
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 13, 2021
content:
The media could not be loaded.
                



This is my second USB C hub from UtechSmart and I've been very happy with both. The previous version (B07KYL58Q1) was great, but one limitation of that hub was that the HDMI and VGA port could only mirror the display and to connect two monitors to my laptop in extended mode, I had to use an external display driver (B00L3Z7E3W).But this new USB C hub solves that problem because I can connect one monitor to VGA and another monitor to one of the HDMI ports and run both in extended mode. I don't use my laptop screen when connected to monitors, but if I want I can have all 3 (laptop + 2 monitors) in extended mode. This is great for multitasking! And the price of this hub isn't much higher than the previous version so if you're looking for something that works as a hub that lets you run two external monitors in extended mode, get this one. It would have been great if the second HDMI port also supported "extended" display so that 4 monitors (including the laptop screen) could be run in extended mode.  I'm hoping a newer version (or maybe a firmware/driver?) will address this.  The cable is a little short though, would have been nice if it was about a foot long or (even better) detachable so that if the cable breaks over time, it can be easily replaced. Overall, this is a great multi-functional USB C hub - all ports work as they're supposed to and have served me very well paired with my Dell XPS.

author: Taterdude
date: Reviewed in the United States on July 3, 2020
content: The product works as advertised. There is a lot to love about it if you need multiple monitors and USB ports.I have both Mac and Windows machines and for the Mac it cloned the display and that was it as far a monitor goes. BUT...that is EXACTLY what the manufacturer said it would do. That is what I wanted from my tiny MacBook Pro screen, so very happy there.As for windows, I hooked this up to a brand new HP Z-book and attached three monitors to it. I got three a three monitor spread. Two were an extended desktop, so a "double wide" screen image, the third was a separate, image of the desktop. This is exactly what I wanted. This is how it works with the limitations of the HP Z-book and its video card. Other video cards may vary.I also must compliment the manufacturer for listing the compatible products. Many others do not. I saw my machine in the list and got the results I expected. I could not be happier with this product.I am an IT person. So, here is a tip for those running this hub with HP. Use the Windows monitor set up to configure the monitors once you have this hub connected. You must do this. The hub will not automatically do it for you. Once you are set up, here is a tip. If you restart your computer, upon the completion of that restart, the hub will simply clone your desktop across both or all three monitors. To go back to the settings you put in, simply unplug the hub from the computer, then plug it back in. All will be reset just as you wanted it and had it set.This product works as advertised. USB hubs also work with both Mac and Windows.

author: Roy Samuel
date: Reviewed in the United States on November 16, 2020
content: Update 10/27/2021 - This device continues to impress! Ended up getting a second one for a new laptop I'm using to work from home (Dell Inspiron 13 [5310]) and can confirm that I can extend two monitors via one of the Thunderbolt 4 ports on the laptop. The only thing it doesn't do is power USB-A peripherals such as a keyboard or mouse. Aside from that, I'm very happy with it and feel it's a great device for the price for those who need additional ports/are working from home.Bought this to allow my daughter to use an external monitor and keyboard/mouse with her Pixelbook Go while still letter her charge (when needed) while she was remote learning for school.  This was the perfect attachment! It is as plug and play as you can get and does not run hot! Granted, it just has a single monitor and a wireless keyboard/mouse receiver on it, but it is precisely want my daughter needed to have a functional setup while attending school remotely.  What's nice is that when she isn't using it, I can grab it and use it with other USB-C devices I have to take advantage of the other ports!  I tested this with my work laptop and confirmed that I could run a dual-monitor setup, which is huge in being able to replicate (as best as possible anyway) my office setup while working from home during the pandemic.  All in all, you can't go wrong with this device - can't speak for older devices, but if you're running fairly recent tech in the last couple years then this device should work for you without any issues.  Highly recommend it!

author: G
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 19, 2019
content: I got this as an Ipad/Desktop add-on. For my desktop, My Wacom Cintiq 16 has USB-c ports which are more useful with different ports. more USB-A ports are nice and are useful and the Micro SD/ SD slots work well. I don't have a need for the Ethernet port BUT when plugged into my Ipad Pro 2018 it does pop up as 10/100/1000 possible connection. Officially, it does NOT support  Ipad Pros, but it kind of does. the ports all work for the Ipad, plug in a micro sd/SD card and it will open up the photos app to import pictures. If you plug in a keyboard to the USB- A ports (normal USB ports) the keyboard will work. If you plug in any USB hard drive/ flash drive it will not work correctly but that is an apple issue. My two complaints are minor, I wish it had an AUX port. More Apple devices are ditching AUX and adding that in somewhere would have been a better move than a micro sd slot since most micro SD cards come with an adapter to SD.  It also seems to require additional power when connecting the Ipad to a monitor, which is fine since it has USB-C power in, but you need to plug it in this order: HDMI, USB-C Power, USB-C to the device.Edit/Update: After talking to their support we discovered that a setting on the ipad needed to be turned on and then it would support 4k. Works great just wish it was a little cheaper.Pros:Works wellFast connectionsEasy to useNice/ Simple Design4k SupportCons:No Aux porttoo many video output options (and using VGA downgrades the HDMI to only 1080p option for all monitors)Gets fairly warm when used for long periods of time under heavy workloads.

author: Brian B
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 20, 2020
content: I bought this "hub" in order to "dock" my Lenovo t480 laptop and support 2 HDMI monitors for my "work at home" setup. I shopped very carefully before selecting this unit, and double checked that it supported the features I wanted. The enclosure body is aluminum and feels smooth and solid. The "dongle" is long enough. To this hub, I've connected 2 HDMI monitors, a wired network connection, and 2 USB cables to the 2 monitors where each monitor has a USB 2.0 Hub. My laptop charger plugs directly into the hub. There are still extra USB 3.0 ports and SD slots available. When I "dock" my laptop, I just plug this USB hub into my laptop's USB-C port ... and I'm done. The laptop uses the USB-C data connection to connect to the wired internet, the HDMI monitors, and the various USB peripherals. The hub powers the laptop and charges the battery.A couple of notes. The first time I plugged things together the laptop complained about not having all the power it expected , but after a few seconds the issue cleared and hasn't returned. I don't know if it was a delay negotiating to a more powerful power-delivery setting, or it the laptop charger was not keeping up with demand. The laptop power supply is only rated for 65w, Just in case, I've separately ordered a 100-watt PD charger and cable that I expect to use when I'm "docked".A couple reviews suggest the hub might get quite hot during use. That hasn't been an issue for me. In my setup, the hub has good circulation and is only warm to the touch when it is running.

author: Common_Sense621
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 4, 2022
content: *** UPDATED ***I contacted the seller and they let me know that wireless keyboard/mouse operate on the same frequency as the device and recommended I get a USB 2.0 Extension Cable to move the wireless fob a small distance from the device.  I figured it made no sense but tried it anyway... IT WORKED!  I just typed a few work emails and had absolutely no issues.  All things resolved!------------------I purchased this as a hub for the 3 laptops we have in our house.  I plugged in 2 monitors through the HDMI and 1 USB fob for a Logitech Wireless Keyboard and Mouse combo. The monitors work fine but the keyboard/mouse work intermittently.  Sometimes they work, other times they do not.  If I unplug the fob and plug it directly into a USB port on the laptop - they work great!So, in my experience - if you are looking for a hub to have 2 monitors, this can work!  But if you want to use any other peripherals, than this is probably not the right choice.

author: Steve Evans
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 20, 2020
content: I purchased this for when my Dell hub was stopped working after a nearby lighting strike.  I needed something that could handle 1 HDMI monitor, 1 VGA monitor, and my Surface Book 2's laptop screen (12" I7, 16GB ram, dGPU Nvidia 1050) for a total of 3 screens which this does nicely.  The first thing I tried was to run Minecraft on the HDMI, OneNote on the VGA, and a GoToMeeting on the laptop screen.  Worked perfectly with no lag and looks as good as ever.I also needed a GigE port, an USB ports for an external composite microphone, mouse, Jabra speaker, and a USB fan (why not!).  It connects to my USB C port on my Surface Book and sits several inches behind it using the included pigtail connector.  I will likely use the USB C port as well to charge some items but have not as yet.I like the metal finish too.  Looks nice.  It came with a soft bag to put it in for travel which I would normally plan to use, but with Covid-19, who knows when I'll travel again!  There was also a nice little USB "card" that came in it which loads a video showing there different monitor configurations, what works and what might not.All-in-all, I'm very pleased with this purchase so far (1 day).  I'll come back if anything changes or I learn anything else helpful.  As it stands, I can recommend this product for the uses I've detailed.

author: SoCalDogfather
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 7, 2020
content: Here's the proposition: Trade away the two USB-C ports on the left side of your Macbook Pro and a few ounces of weight, get back one of those USB-c ports, three USB 3 ports, plus SD and Micro-SD slots. Sound like a good trade-off to you? Yep - thought so. That's what this handy little device does, and does it without any undue fuss. It's got a solid metal build, so it's highly unlikely to fly into pieces when (not if) you drop it (hey, sh*t happens!). Best of all, no cables to fuss with.As with almost anything, there are some negatives, which in this case are really a matter of a certain amount of hair splitting. If you have a cover on your MBP, it will have to come off to accommodate this adapter. I wish the ports could be just a bit longer to prevent this inconvenience, but it's a fair enough trade-off for such a low price point. I would also wish for an HDMI port on the back end of this, as is the case with many such adapters. Again, price point renders this kind of moot. You want all the bells and whistles? Pay up. I am happy with what this adapter can do and consider the trade-offs to be more than reasonable. I have a more equipped adapter (effectively a docking station) for my desk, and this one for my laptop bag, and that works just fine for me!Highly recommended - just be aware of what you're getting (and not getting) so as to avoid unnecessary disappointment.

author: AJ Whitney
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 4, 2020
content: I'm lucky enough to be able to do most of my work from home, but because I live close to work and never really got around to getting a good home office set up, most of the time I work from my office/cubicle. But when the pandemic hit and we transitioned to working from home full time, I was suddenly forced to adapt to this new reality. I quickly realized that my eyes weren't up for staring at a laptop monitor for 8 hours a day, and a single 24" monitor wasn't going to get the job done. Fortunately, my laptop was new enough that I could connect a USB C dock to it, and I found the UtechSmart Triple Display USB Type C Adapter Docking Station here on Amazon and that's been working great since I got it six weeks ago. I little later I picked up a 60 watt USB C Charger, and I now leave that plugged in to the docking station so that I only have to plug one cable USB C cable into my laptop when it is time to work. That frees up my original charger that I can leave by my recliner when I'm using my laptop for non work-related things in the evenings. The docking station has worked great, and my only gripe would be that the cable from the dock to my laptop  could be a few inches longer. This is a very minor quibble, and doesn't detract from its usefulness.

content: This is the second one of these I have purchased. Both do exactly what I wanted them to do - enable the laptop to project on multiple displays. The first one was purchased because it said it would work with a "Chromebook" where some of the others did not mention that. It has been over a year without an issues with it. After the success with the Chromebook, I purchased a second docking station for another laptop. It performed the same as the other. Something to note - if your laptop doesn't have a LAN port and it is needed - this docking station can be used as an adapter, for that it does have a LAN female port.

author: FrankHM
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 1, 2020
content: I purchased the UtechSmart Triple Display UDB docking station to enable me to work from home more efficiently.  My setup is two HP 24f 23.8" IPS LED FSH Freesync monitors, a Dell Latitude 7480 laptop and a Logictech wireless keyboard and mouse.  I also purchased a 87W USB C power adapter so that I would only have one plug (from the docking station) going into the laptop.  Initially, I had an issue with getting both monitors to work in extended display mode (so they each acted independently).  After talking to UtechSmart support, they quickly sent me a new docking station and now everything works perfectly.  You don't have to have the power adapter, but it is nice not to have to plug your laptop into a wall socket and just have the single USB-C plug going from the docking station to the laptop.  I use 5 of the ports on the docking station - The two HDMI ports for the monitors, one USB port for the bluetooth keyboard and mouse, one for the USB-C power supply and the last is to charge my headphones for work calls.  This setup has helped me be as efficient at home as I am when I'm in the office.  I'll keep this setup even after I'm able to return to the office for those days when I need to work from home.

author: Ryan Vaughn
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 16, 2022
content: Works perfect for my setup. I have 2 monitors, 1 mouse, 1 keyboard, and 1 LED ring light. I leave my laptop open so it’s essentially a 3-display setup. No functionality issues whatsoever. Plug and play. Couldn’t have been any easier.Takes 1-2 seconds longer then my laptop to “wake” after being asleep but I experience no lag after it comes on. Gets a little warm to the touch but nothing alarming.The weight of all the cables plugged into the port tends to pull the whole port down and unplug it from the laptop. It never unplugged itself but the wire looked strained so I attached the port to the back of my desk with heavy duty Velcro. Now I can simply unplug without worrying about the port falling behind the desk. The laptop plug stays right there to plug back in when I get back from a work trip…or the beach ;)

author: David Ehmer
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 19, 2020
content: Works as advertised.  The hub got here fast and was packaged just fine.  I got a Dell Latitude 7300 laptop for work.  At my office they got me a new Dell docking station to go with it.  The dell docking station is huge, has fewer ports than this one, and is more than twice as expensive.  I was a little hesitant to go with this simpler one from UtechSmart, but I figured I'd give it a try.  It plugs straight into my laptop and provides power to the laptop as well as lets me use both extra monitors AND my laptop monitor (3) at the same time, which is exactly what I wanted.  I was also able to hard wire in my printer via USB.  I did have to buy a separate USB-C cord and block to power the hub, but even with that, it was still way less expensive than the dell docking station.  Here is the USB-C power cord I got.  Need to make sure it has enough power so that the hub can support your laptop power (this one has 100W).  My wife as a MacBook Air and just as UtechSmart said, the hub does support it, but I can only duplicate the screen on my extra monitors with a MacBook.  I recommend this hub.https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B087FRLCHL/ref=ppx_yo_dt_b_asin_image_o02_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1

author: Paul
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 10, 2020
content: When I purchased this, I was unsure of it's viability as you can never be too sure of any product you buy anymore. But  I needed a USB-C hub for my new MacBook Pro and after looking at the reviews, I decided to give it a try. When it arrived, I was very happy with the quality of the hub and even more so that it matched my MacBook perfectly. It is lightweight and slips in my briefcase and is always there when I need it. For the price, it is a great buy for anyone needing a good USB-C hub. I especially like that I can have several standard USB devices connected at the same time while my USB-C charging cable is plugged in. The card readers work perfectly and you can even use the hub bidirectionally (see photos). I have only had minor issues, but I think it was due to the OS build for the MacBook Pro's affecting the USB-C ports.Pros:LightweightFunctionalAluminum bodyMatches the new MacBooksAffordableCons:Only one USB-C portFeels too lightweight - almost too lightweightNo HDMI/Lightning out for A/VOther than those little things, this is a decent hub and I would recommend purchasing two - they are easy to forget at home!

author: DrSus
date: Reviewed in the United States on September 22, 2020
content: I bought this hub to be able to run all my USB accessories, two monitors, and charge my laptop by only plugging one cable into the laptop. I have a Dell XPS 13, 9300 model built in 2020. Initially I had problems with getting the monitors to work. After reading the manual that comes on the USB flash drive, I upgraded the HDMI cables to high speed 8K. While it was necessary it didn't really help that much. I also bought a 90W power adapter for the hub to power it and charge the laptop. Still, the hub worked very unstable with the computer. Biggest problem was the laptop would recognize the monitors, but would not display video. Half the time I would plug the hub in and everything worked fine and the other half it would take 4 or 5 tries and a restart to get them working.As I figured out the problem was not the hub. Dell has released two BIOS updates since July. The last one that was released in early September 2020 was huge and helped a lot. Now the hub works properly 90% of the time. I am hoping for more Dell software upgrades to stabilize the USBC connections on the video side some more. Over all the hub is a good product and does what I want it to do.

author: 1brotha
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 23, 2020
content: This docking station can support 3 monitors. It has 2 HDMI ports and a VGA port. At this time I have 2 HDMI monitors connected due to limited work space, but I have had these 2 monitors and my TV, which has a VGA port, connected just to test and confirm the device can manage 3 monitors - see pictures. I use the one docking station for 2 laptops, the work laptop and the personal laptop without having to change multiple cables from 1 laptop to the other. My Ethernet cable is connected directly into the RJ45 port on the docking station (you do not have to use the RJ45 port on the device, but it's there if yo need it). My keyboard/mouse dongle is plugged into a USB port on the docking station. When I want to switch laptops I just unplug the docking station from the Thunderbolt port on one laptop and put it into the Thunderbolt port on the other laptop. That's it and everything just works. It's small and light weight and takes up very little desk space, (picture with contact lens case on top for size comparison) but it could be mounted on the back of the desk or under the desktop with Velcro strips. I highly recommend this device.

author: Bill Terwilliger
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 20, 2019
content: As the owner of a Macbook Pro 2016, I know how important a good hub is, since the computer itself isn't useable without one or two.In fact, one brand of hub I have been using before, did not even deliver enough power to use my external keyboard. While this hub powers my keyboard and two old external hard drives.Also I find the data throughput is not limited by the hub which can be the case. The hub is as fast as the cables and drives allow on the few tests I have done so far, although I cannot get the USB C Thunderbolt to plug in to the USB C port on it.But its very useful for my older hard drives, keyboard, Yeti Blue Mic and all my other non Thunderbolt peripherals.Also it hasn't failed yet. Other, more expensive hubs with less ports, would often fail or become intermittent after a couple of weeks. This has been reliable for daily use since I got it at least a month ago.I would totally get this one. I have a drawer full of other ones most of which don't work. But this one handles most of my critical peripherals leaving 3 USB-C, thunderbolt ports open for my eGPU and fast external drives.

date: Reviewed in the United States on October 21, 2020
content: Was very enthusiastic about the features, functionality and specs. Could not get the VGA to work at all. Was disappointed and returned.update:This UtechSmart Docking Station offers fantastic functionality and loads of features especially with my Lenovo Gen 7 X1 that only has two USB A ports. I needed the Utech version with the VGA port to use with an older 17” VGA monitor.My initial disappointment that the old VGA monitor would not work with the unit received was short-lived thanks to the very efficient and caring Utech Customer Care representative who took the initiative and reached out to me to help.The replacement Docking Station works flawlessly and essentially turns my ultra-portable business notebook into fully functional desktop computer with multiple USB ports, card readers and 2 HDMI ports – not to mention pass-thru power delivery and charging with the X1 standard USB C AC charger.  All of this is in a good-looking, sturdy and very portable package that is easy to connect and get things up and running on the road. My thanks to Utech for standing behind their sophisticated Docking Station and their determination to help me to get the benefit of their great product.

author: Jesse Clayton Erickson
date: Reviewed in the United States on December 11, 2020
content: When covid sent employees to work at home we had to have all of the technology and tools that the office had, and more importantly we had to be able to connect it as easily as before.After spending a lot of time researching and comparing options I settled on this. The price was very good compared to many other options and it wasn't going to take up a lot of desktop real-estate.It's been two months and so far there have been no issues. It is literally plug and play easy. When the laptop needs to be disconnected from two monitors, LAN, camera and other peripherals it's just one cord. Everything else stays plugged in but this is what a docking station should do.It is very small, surprisingly small actually but that's ok. The materials and construction feel good but it is incredibly light so if you're going to be carrying it around you'll hardly notice it.All in all I'm very happy with it. It does what I expect for a very good price and as long as it keeps doing it its will stay a 5 star item.

author: Dr. Doctor
date: Reviewed in the United States on August 18, 2020
content: I purchased the UtechSmart Macbook Pro Multiple Adapter shortly after purchasing my MacBook Pro because I feared that the Apple Thunderbolt ports, the only kind that exists on the Macbook, would limit me from using peripherals that used regular USB ports. So I purchased it, and am I glad I did. First, the little adapter is so well made. It is lightweight but does not feel cheap or low quality at all. The plugs for the MacBook ports are in a pair on the adapter and connect snugly into place. Once in place, I find the best thing about the adapter is it lets me plug my iPhone USB port into the adapter so I can charge my iPhone while using the MacBook. The adapter also has slots for both Micro and SD card chips for the camera buffs among us.  I was very impressed as well with the documentation in the package. People have gotten away from paper instructions but these, like the adapter, are compact and high quality. The adapter is light, easy to carry, and now lives in my laptop backpack, as a valued and excellent accessory to my Mac. It is worth every penny.

author: Hannah Markley
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 26, 2020
content: I work as a video content producer for a company. Every week I have two SD cards worth of footage and one microSD card with audio files to upload to my internal hard drive for editing as well as two external hard drives for a back-up. With this adapter, I can plug in two external hard drives with the two side-by-side USB ports, I can put one SD card and one microSD card directly into the card slots, AND I had a standalone SD card reader and USB-to-lightning adapter from my last workflow that I can plug the second SD card in, AND I can still be charging my MacBook on the other side of my computer. It speeds up my work flow SO MUCH as I can transfer and upload all my footage at once to THREE different locations from THREE separate cards. Total game change. PLUS, the last adaptor I had like this was more of a "dongle" design, so it always seemed really floppy and unstable. This one is super stable as it plugs in in two places. Definitely worth your money! I've been using it for two months so far and it's worked flawlessly! Plus it's pretty tiny. Wins all around!

author: Nathan Rodgers
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 20, 2022
content: Product worked great for 2-3 months until it quit working. I was able to connect 2 monitors to my laptop until it randomly stopped allowing two monitors to be connected at the same time. Although my product failed the customer service department made it right.

author: elektrisches schaf
date: Reviewed in Germany on January 23, 2024
content: Die Hülle hat im Gegensatz zu vielen anderen Modellen sofort gepasst und auch nicht die Schutzfolie vom Frontbildschirm aufgeschoben oder angerissen. Auch fand ich gut, dass auf der Rückseite die Ausbuchtung für die Kameralinsen aus einem Stück besteht, wodurch ich die vorher bereits angebrachten Schutzlinsen dranlassen konnte, die ansonsten bei vielen anderen Hüllen nicht in die "Löcher" reinpassen würden.Einen kleinen Abzug hinterlasse ich wegen einer sehr persönlichen Einschätzung: während die Oberfläche der Hülle an sich sehr schön und edel wirkt, ist der Rand der Hülle, also was am Ende auf der Seite des Handys ist, leider sehr "plastikig" vom Gefühl her und noch dazu leicht glänzend, was m.E. nicht zum ansonsten edlen Rest der Hülle passt - ist aber wie gesagt nur eine persönliche Einschätzung :)

author: Bo
date: Reviewed in the United States on January 5, 2024
content: I just needed a clear case for my ipad mini without bulking it up. This clear case was easy to install and does have a slot groove on the side specifically for adding an apple pencil 2 which does magnetically attaches well and will charge with this case in place. I like to use my ipad mini with as less bulk as possible and this case adds minimal bulk and allows easy attaching and charging of my apple pencil 2 when needed and I can set it aside when I don't. Other cases have a added width to their case specifically for slotting and protecting the ipad mini which adds bulk that I don't need so I like this case because its less bulky. Great case at an affordable price should be on your short list if you need a simple clear case for your ipad mini.

author: Stephen C
date: Reviewed in the United States on March 16, 2024
content: Ok, when i first got it out of the box, I was a bit skeptical. I had a 2 piece case in the past and didn't like it because the top popped off easily, but the MATEKXY folks were a little smarter and put a thin double stick adhesive on the inside of the top piece. This definitely keeps it on and the magnets that keep the case enclosed are insanely strong. I took one star off because it is a little bit heavier, but the trade off is worth it as i feel confident that if I drop my airpods that the case will stay shut. Another positive is compared to the silicone that the plastic of this case isn't super smooth, but isn't tacky either, so getting them in and out of your pocket is a breeze, but you can still hold onto the case without feeling like you have butter fingers.

author: ReviewsReviews
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 11, 2024
content: I bought this to cover my airPods Pro case and I am very happy with it. The bottom of the cover fits like a glove. It has adequately sized ports for the cord and a dedicated area for the button operation.The edges of the top and bottom of the case a beveled away from eachother so they don't interrupt with the opening and closing of the case, but because it is such a tight fit my airPods Pro case does not beep when it's opened anymore. This is because the lid, although it opens enough to get the airPods out does not open 100% completely and this keeps the beeper from going off.The top half of the cover attaches to the airPods case via a small strip of 3M double sided tape that you assemble when put it together. This is a good idea because it would just fall off otherwise.The case also comes with a lanyard and a carabiner clip for your keychain or otherwise. Both of these items are  good quality and I don't worry at all about them breaking.The case is made of a thick and durable rubberized plastic that I would trust to just about any drop. This is a VERY durable case that is going to add a lot of protection to your valued airPods. It has a futuristic and angled design that is very contemporary and looks really nice. I haven't noticed that I have found the case intrusive in any way, although people who put their airPods in their pocket may find it a little more difficult to get in there due to the rubberized case, and increased size dimensions.The case comes with a cleaning kit that I have used already. The brush works nice for cleaning debris from the grills, and the pick works well to remove debris from any of the grooves on the pods or the case. The tube brush is extremely convenient to have when cleaning the bays of the airPods case where the airPods fit.  All of these brushes are well made and should last a long time.NOTE - I did not check this device for wireless charging compatibility, but it does say that it works with wireless compatible devices. If it doesn't the case is easy enough to remove if you're set on using wireless charging with the device. I just prefer wired charging because it is so much faster.Overall, I am extremely satisfied with this purchase and I would buy again, and suggest them to anyone looking for a protective case for their airPods Pro earbuds.5 star rating for being a great overall product, and including the extras I mentioned above.-Highly suggested item.If you like this review please feel free to look at some of the other reviews I have provided for products here on Amazon. Also, if you've found this review to be helpful, please give it a positive rating. I try to provide the most accurate, unbiased reviews for everyone.Thanks for reading, and I hope you enjoy your new item.

author: ShallWe?Family
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 16, 2024
content: At the current price of $9.99 this AirPods Pro case is a great value. It comes with the case itself, two types of clips (you can choose depending on your preference,) a small tool to remove the case should it get stuck, and two cleaning tools.The case itself is in two pieces. The pieces are magnetic to each other though, which is nice. The top piece does have a plastic piece with a tab to remove and it’s sticky, to stick onto your AirPods top. I chose to not remove the plastic though (I just cut the tab off) because I worry it will get stuck on. I haven’t had any problems with it falling off. It comes with a small tool that you put in the charger port and push up with one hand and push the case down with the other should the case be difficult to get off. I’m not having trouble removing the case but it’s a nice touch. I have had a different case get stuck on. I learned that you can do the same thing by plugging your air pods into the charger and pull the case down while pressing up on the charger.The case is one of the bulkier cases I’ve used but it seems the most protective. It’s MagSafe and works with my Belkin MagSafe charger.  It does have a spot in the back that you can push in to pair it to another device without removing the case. You do have to press it hard though.They’re a little bulky and not the most attractive case. They seem very protective though. They look exactly like the pictures shown though so you know what you’re getting. This was not worth deducting a star to me.The included cleaning tools are nice and help you get into the little crevices of the AirPods and the charging case.It’s a great case and a great value!

author: i1DERProductions
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 26, 2024
content: My airpods pro 2nd gen are heavily scratched and whatnot from use outisde of a case and I regret not having protected it, but life happens.This case feels solid and the magnets are on par! I just wish there was a way to stick it to semi-vertical watch chargers, but oh well. It certainly sticks to magsafe chargers at any angle well enough to make up for it. The lid magnet is also very strong, almost too much, but I'd rather too much than not enough. Going 30mph on a scooter with bumps and jolts while this case is dangling feels secure, contained and protected... uhhhh... riiiight.The holes for sound and lights is perfect and the pairing button is accessible.The included strap and clip feel great and easy to use, but I may consider coming up with some kind of magnetic quick mount with a tension clip or something, take advantage of the magnets cus why not?

content: Finally - after several tries, I have finally found a case for my airpods that is sturdy, and allows me to charge the ear buds in the case. author: Kelly Jo
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 17, 2024
content: There are 2 curtain panels in my order. The product listing does state that these are background curtains, or also known as backdrop curtains, for the purpose of photography or celebrations. In my opinion, they would indeed work just fine for this purpose, as well as for social media video background curtains. They would likely even do well as a normal window curtain set. However, do know that since they come as a 2 panel set, depending on how they are hung and positioned, the seperation gap could be made visible or not visible. It's just personal preference, really.These curtains are definitely long enough to be used as a full length, or near full length, backdrop, depending on staging and user height. They also are plenty long enough to be used for the standard full size window. While other color options or bundle packages may be available at other times, my own order contained a solid and evenly applied color commonly refered to as baby blue.The fabric of these curtains is somewhat thin and slightly rough textured. The stitching is also slightly thin threaded, with thin seam margins, but otherwise still looks well done. It is for these last 2 traits that this curtain set gets 4 out of 5 stars.

author: Kelly Jo
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 17, 2024
content: There are 2 curtain panels in my order. The product listing does state that these are background curtains, or also known as backdrop curtains, for the purpose of photography or celebrations. In my opinion, they would indeed work just fine for this purpose, as well as for social media video background curtains. They would likely even do well as a normal window curtain set. However, do know that since they come as a 2 panel set, depending on how they are hung and positioned, the seperation gap could be made visible or not visible. It's just personal preference, really.These curtains are definitely long enough to be used as a full length, or near full length, backdrop, depending on staging and user height. They also are plenty long enough to be used for the standard full size window. While other color options or bundle packages may be available at other times, my own order contained a solid and evenly applied color commonly refered to as baby blue.The fabric of these curtains is somewhat thin and slightly rough textured. The stitching is also slightly thin threaded, with thin seam margins, but otherwise still looks well done. It is for these last 2 traits that this curtain set gets 4 out of 5 stars.

author: MumSabrina
date: Reviewed in the United States on April 27, 2024
content: This backdrop is pretty nice as far as richness of color, for the size of it, for the price, and for the finishing. It's all finished nicely, no loose threads or snags. It is best for indoors.The fabric is more of medium weight, but on the lighter side. It's hard to describe for me, sorry.I think that the price is fair for such a massive backdrop in such a bright color. It is good quality and I'm sure that I'll be using it for years. I like the zip bag included. It's just clear plastic, but it'll help me keep this organized and visible, as well as clean.

content: My previous iPad case did not have a pencil holder built-in to it, so the pencil just dangles on the side, so I thought I would try one of these designs that have a cubby hole for it.While I do like having a little protection to keep the pencil from falling off, this design doesn't allow for the quick removal of the pencil. Seems to me that the designers of this never actually used it, as in daily usage, I constantly set and remove the pencil quite frequently and this case does not allow for a quick removal. The pencil is securely stuck in and is quite fiddly to remove.To remediate this I actually took a pair of scissors and removed some of the cage, but that ended up with leaving a sharp edge that is not comfortable.To sum it up, I only recommend this case for someone who does not attach/reattach the pencil is is mostly concerned with keeping the pencil secure. If that is your use-case, then this is probably worthy of all 5 stars.

content: This is like a phone case for your 7th Gen iPad Pro 13" - Thi protects the edges and the back and has a slot for your Apple pencil Pro to charge. The front is open ( like a phone case ). It does a nice job protecting the edges of the iPad. It's thin and light ( doesn't add much bulk at all ) and has a nice integration for penicil pro placement. The back is see through clear so it does show fingerprints. The pictures make it look more finger print prone than reality ( glare in my office ) - I recommend this case if you really want a slim and light case and don't need a cover for the screen. This is how I like my iPad and I covered the screen with a screen protector.

author: J. Washum
date: Reviewed in the United States on May 27, 2024
content: This is a very minimal case for the new M4 iPad Pro 13” if that is what you want, this product is fantastic!The fit is tight but it was little weight. While I did not drop my iPad on purpose the corners seem very cushioned and would withstand minimal impacts. The back, while quite clear and reflective (as you can see from the picture) really allows the back of the iPad to stand out and it is completely clear - looks fantastic.The pencil cutout is in the correctly place and allowed mine to charge while holding the pencil securely. Almost too secure at first. Pushing on one end will remove the pencil easily but it took a few times to get this down but I had no issues once figuring this out.The cast to me is much like a phone case - great back and side protection. All the buttons work great and it doesn’t feel like it will come off easily.While there is a lip protecting the front, like most phone cases it’s only about 1 to 1.5mm above the screen meaning that I would put solid protector on the front class while using this as my primary case - which I have done anyway.There aren’t many cases yet and this one is quite solid, just know there is not a lot to protect the front of your iPad. It definitely doesn’t add a lot of weight but does make it much easier to hold while using as a tablet. This is now my primary case when not docked to my keyboard.Very pleased!

I love how thin my iPad is - but I really didn't love the Apple folio case this year. :( I tried to love it, but found myself looking for alternative cases quickly. This one was one of the first released, and looked worth trying, even at the low cost. I was VERY pleasantly surprised - and plan to use this as my main case now! It looks good, feels good, and most of all is LIGHT. Finally, what the new iPad deserves. UNDER 5g! :) I included a video review showing the comparison - but overall this is a great case for those looking for a minimal closer to no-case feel. It offers "just enough" protection to make me feel good while keeping me from losing my pencil that follows me everywhere. Great value for the money, and a wonderful minimalist choice.

author: George Collier
date: Reviewed in Canada on June 13, 2024
content: I use my ipad every day during the summer and fall to record research data outdoors in the field.  I need a case that is sturdy enough to be dropped in the dirt a few time a season, but also something that is not so bulky it is a problem to carry and also to write on with the apple pencil.  I find that this case very much fulfills my requirements.  The built in pen holder is a great addition as it keeps the pen securely in place while still allowing it to charge, without me having to worry about it being lost.  I find that the added padding from this case is just right, there are small bump outs on the corners to give a bit of extra cushion should you drop it on a hard surface.  The buttons on the tablet work fine through the case and I have not detected any false presses like I have experienced from other cases.  I also like the size of the cutout fro the charge port, this allows me to use a good quality charge cable without needing to remove the case.  The design of the lip that holds the tablet in place was also well done, as it does not interfere with most glass screen protectors.  The look of this case is also quite slick, the clear back lets you retain the look of the ipad.Overall I think this is a great case for most users.

author: Natasha M.
date: Reviewed in the United States on June 2, 2024
content: Was easy to install. I actually really like the feel. When I’m holding my IPad in the case. Fit snug on IPad Pro 13inch. I think it would be semi durable. Not the most protective case ever. Price is okay. If you’re looking for a lightweight case. And wanna keep everything on the thin side. This case is great. The biggest con which in my photos I tried to show was that around the cut outs of the speaker it’s very thin and bendy. So when u hold it where those points are on the case you kinda pull out the edges a little bit. Also the one side where the Apple pencil goes. They must of made it kinda thinner so it was still compatible. So that part is very bendy also. And the last thing is I just wish they had made lifts around the camera part. It is flush with the iPad and that always makes me nervous. Even with the little things that could be changed to improve this case. I would buy this case again. I definitely like how it looks that it is clear. It feels really nice to hold. And looks great.

content: Was easy to install. I actually really like the feel. When I’m holding my IPad in the case. Fit snug on IPad Pro 13inch. I think it would be semi durable. Not the most protective case ever. I definitely like how it looks that it is clear. It feels really nice to hold. And looks great.
